{"title_page": "Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3", "text_new": "{{spanish name 2|P\u00e1ez|Vilar\u00f3}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 \n|image       = Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3.jpg\n|image_size  =\n|caption     = Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 in 2009.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1923|11|01|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2014|2|24|1923|11|01|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Punta Ballena]], Uruguay\n|occupation  = Painter, potter, sculptor, muralist, writer, composer, constructor. \n|nationality = [[Uruguayan]] \n|spouse      = Madel\u00f3n Rodr\u00edguez G\u00f3mez (1955&ndash;61)<br/>Annette Deussen (m. 1989)\n|partner     = \n|children    = Carlos Miguel, Mercedes, [[Ag\u00f3 P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3|Ag\u00f3]], Sebasti\u00e1n, Florencio, and Alejandro. \n|signature   =\n|website     = {{URL|http://www.carlospaezvilaro.com}}\n}}\n'''Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3''' (1 November 1923 \u2013 24 February 2014) was a [[Uruguay]]an abstract artist, painter, potter, sculptor, muralist, writer, composer and constructor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-carlos-paez-vilaro-20140226-story.html|title=Carlos Paez Vilaro dies at 90; Uruguayan mural artist and musician|date=2014-02-26|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegreatcat.org/the-cat-in-art-and-photos-2/cats-in-art-20th-century/carlos-paez-vilaro-1923-2014-uruguayan/|title=Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 (1923 \u2013 2014, Uruguayan)|date=2017-05-12|website=THE GREAT CAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nCarlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 was born in [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]], in 1923. He took up [[drawing]] in 1939 and relocated to [[Buenos Aires]], where he worked as a [[printing]] apprentice in the industrial [[Barracas, Buenos Aires|Barracas]] section of the Argentine capital. Returning to Montevideo in the late 1940s, he developed an interest in [[Afro-Uruguayan]] culture.<ref name=\":0\" /> Settling in Montevideo's primarily black neighbourhood of \"Mediomundo\" (\"Half-World\"), he studied the [[Candombe|Candomb\u00e9]] and [[Comparsa]] dances characteristic to the culture.<ref>[http://www.carlospaezvilaro.com/cpv/home/home/index.php?menu=sub1_2&t=secciones&secc=10257&sub=10260 Artist's bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911192328/http://www.carlospaezvilaro.com/cpv/home/home/index.php?menu=sub1_2&t=secciones&secc=10257&sub=10260 |date=September 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHe composed numerous musical pieces in the two genres and conducted an orchestra. His group's [[conga]]s and [[Bongo drum|bongos]] were decorated with their leader's own thematic drawings, as well. His interest in the culture later led him to [[Brazil]], home to the western hemisphere's largest population of [[Afro-Brazilian|African descent]]. P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 was invited to exhibit some of this work by the Director of the [[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris|Modern Art Museum of Paris]], [[Jean Cassou]], in 1956. He traveled to [[Dakar]], [[Senegal]], later that year - his first visit to Africa.<ref name=lanacion>[http://www.lanacion.com.ar/nota.asp?nota_id=537743 ''La Naci\u00f3n'' {{in lang|es}}]</ref>\n\nHe was one of the \"Grupo de los 8\", a movement of Uruguayan artists formed in 1958 together with Oscar Garc\u00eda Reino, Miguel \u00c1ngel Pareja, Ra\u00fal Pavlovsky, Lincoln Presno, Am\u00e9rico Sposito, Alfredo Testoni and Julio Verdie in order to promote new tendencies in painting. In 1960 they were invited by art critic [[Rafael Squirru]] to join the international exhibition at the [[Buenos Aires Museum of Modern Art]] (of which he was creator and first director) with artists such as [[Willem De Kooning]], [[Roger Hilton]] and [[Lucio Fontana]]. The experimental tendencies of the Grupo de los 8 have since gained a place of unquestionable relevance not only in the panorama of Uruguayan art but also at an international level, some of their works forming part of museums and collections worldwide.\n\nIncreasingly well-known, P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 was commissioned in 1959 to create a mural for a tunnel connecting a new annex to the [[Organization of American States]]' [[Washington, DC]] headquarters, the Pan American Union building. Originally intended to be no more than {{convert|15|m}} in length, the completed mural (''Roots of Peace'') measured {{convert|155|m}} long and nearly {{convert|2|m}} high when unveiled in 1960. Extensive damage from humidity prompted the artist to repaint the mural in 1975.<ref>[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-25153240_ITM Access My Library: The Bright side of the tunnel]</ref>\n[[File:Casapueblo.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Casapueblo Uruguay|Casapueblo]], his \"livable sculpture\" and best-known creation near [[Punta del Este]], has been a leading tourist destination in Uruguay since the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daylife.com/photo/05LG0cT9Bb1XG |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318075236/http://www.daylife.com/photo/05LG0cT9Bb1XG |archivedate=2012-03-18 }}</ref>]] \nHe purchased a sea-front property on eastern Uruguay's scenic, then-desolate [[Punta Ballena]] in 1958, building a small, wooden lodge that over time became \"[[Casapueblo Uruguay|Casapueblo]]\" (\"House-Village\"). The sprawling compound, a whitewashed cement [[citadel]] reminiscent of [[Mykonos]], was built in stages by the artist to resemble the mud nests created by the region's native [[hornero]] birds, and became his home, [[wikt:atelier|atelier]] and museum.<ref name=\"onsc\">[http://www.onsc.gub.uy/gxpsites/Archivos%5CPublicaciones%5CRevistaONSC%5CR34%5C02.%20Museo%20Casapueblo.pdf ONSC: Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 {{in lang|es}}]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> Though he resided in Casapueblo - his \"livable sculpture\" - by 1968, P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 continued to add on to the structure, at times creating a room for a particular guest. He later opened a section of Casapueblo to tourism as a hotel.<ref name=nueve>[http://nueve-franjas-y-un-sol.blogia.com/2006/072501-carlos-paez-vilaro.php Nueve franjas y un sol {{in lang|es}}] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827111044/http://nueve-franjas-y-un-sol.blogia.com/2006/072501-carlos-paez-vilaro.php |date=2009-08-27 }}</ref><ref name=clarin>[http://www.servicios.clarin.com/notas/jsp/enie/v1/notas/imprimir.jsp?pagid=1718013 ''Clar\u00edn'' {{in lang|es}}] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708163040/http://www.servicios.clarin.com/notas/jsp/enie/v1/notas/imprimir.jsp?pagid=1718013 |date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nP\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 remained active in European and African culture, as well. He remained close with numerous friends from his days in [[Paris]] in the late 1950s, particularly [[Brigitte Bardot]] and [[Pablo Picasso]], and in 1967, established a [[film production]] company (\"Dahlia\") with the help of European industrialists Gerard Leclery and [[Gunther Sachs]].<ref>[http://www.magicasruinas.com.ar/revistero/internacional/internacional-casapueblo-paez-vilaro.htm P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3: Un personaje de novela. ''Gente''(20 February 1969) {{in lang|es}}]</ref> He traveled in numerous [[West Africa]]n nations to make a documentary, ''Batouk'', with director Jean-Jacques Manigot and poet [[Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0218026/ imdb: ''Batouk'']</ref> \n\nThe artist's first marriage, to Madel\u00f3n Rodr\u00edguez G\u00f3mez, though brief, produced three children. One of them, [[Carlitos P\u00e1ez|Carlos \"Carlitos\" P\u00e1ez Rodr\u00edguez]], would later join the [[Stella Maris College (Montevideo)|Stella Maris College]] \"Old Christians\" [[Rugby union|Rugby]] team; on 13 October 1972, [[Uruguayan Air Force Flight 571]] carrying the team crashed in the forbidding [[Andes]] range, between [[Chile]] and [[Mendoza Province]], [[Argentina]]. P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 joined the [[search and rescue]] mission for the 45 passengers, of which 16 survived, including his son, with whom he was reunited shortly after their 23 December rescue.<ref>[http://www.viven.com.uy/571/eng/default.asp Viven {{in lang|es}}]</ref> \n\nP\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 experienced difficulties in other areas of his life. He met Annette Deussen, an Argentine tourist, in 1976, and she had his child in 1984. Deussen was married to another man at the time, and the marriage dissolved in 1986; she and P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 married in 1989. Her former spouse, however, continued his legal fight for the child for over a decade, even after P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3's paternity was established by tests.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/1998/10/12/e-03901d.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' (12 October 1998) {{in lang|es}}]</ref> The matter was ultimately resolved in the P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3s' favor in 1999.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/1999/11/07/e-05401d.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' (7 November 1999) {{in lang|es}}]</ref> \n[[File:Works by Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3.jpg|thumb|210px|A number of recent paintings by the artist, on display at Casapueblo.]]\nHe continued to create murals and sculptures for various government offices, corporate headquarters, private homes, and other buildings. He created 12 murals in [[Argentina]], 16 in [[Brazil]], 4 in [[Chad]], 3 in [[Chile]], 4 in [[Gabon]], 11 in the [[United States]], and 30 in his native [[Uruguay]], as well as a scattering of works elsewhere in [[Africa]] and in the [[Polynesian islands]].<ref name=nueve/> He also designed a non-denominational [[chapel]] for a cemetery without crosses or headstones in [[San Isidro, Buenos Aires]] and rebuilt an abandoned house in nearby [[Tigre, Buenos Aires|Tigre]] in 1989 in the manner of Casapueblo; he considered the San Isidro chapel his \"greatest work\".   In his last years the artist divided his time between Casapueblo and \"Bengala,\" his Tigre residence.<ref name=clarin/>\n\nOn 24 February 2014 P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 died at the age of 90 at his home ''Casapueblo'', in Punta Ballena.\n\nHis son stated in reaction to his father's death \"I hope he rests in peace. I've never seen a guy who works that much, and I mean it. He worked up until yesterday.\"<ref>[http://www.montevideo.com.uy/notnoticias_227353_1.html ''Montevideo Portal'' (24 February 2014) {{in lang|es}}] </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.thegreatcat.org/the-cat-in-art-and-photos-2/cats-in-art-20th-century/carlos-paez-vilaro-1923-2014-uruguayan/ Carlos' cats]\n\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paez Vilaro, Carlos}}\n[[Category:Uruguayan muralists]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan painters]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan potters]]\n[[Category:People from Montevideo]]\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan people of Catalan descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Cementerio del Norte, Montevideo]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name 2|P\u00e1ez|Vilar\u00f3}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 \n|image       = Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3.jpg\n|image_size  =\n|caption     = Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 in 2009.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1923|11|01|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2014|2|24|1923|11|01|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Punta Ballena]], Uruguay\n|occupation  = Painter, potter, sculptor, muralist, writer, composer, constructor. \n|nationality = [[Uruguayan]] \n|spouse      = Madel\u00f3n Rodr\u00edguez G\u00f3mez (1955&ndash;61)<br/>Annette Deussen (m. 1989)\n|partner     = \n|children    = Carlos Miguel, Mercedes, [[Ag\u00f3 P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3|Ag\u00f3]], Sebasti\u00e1n, Florencio, and Alejandro. \n|signature   =\n|website     = {{URL|http://www.carlospaezvilaro.com}}\n}}\n'''Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3''' (1 November 1923 \u2013 24 February 2014) was a [[Uruguay]]an abstract artist, painter, potter, sculptor, muralist, writer, composer and constructor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-carlos-paez-vilaro-20140226-story.html|title=Carlos Paez Vilaro dies at 90; Uruguayan mural artist and musician|date=2014-02-26|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegreatcat.org/the-cat-in-art-and-photos-2/cats-in-art-20th-century/carlos-paez-vilaro-1923-2014-uruguayan/|title=Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 (1923 \u2013 2014, Uruguayan)|date=2017-05-12|website=THE GREAT CAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nCarlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 was born in [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]], in 1923. He took up [[drawing]] in 1939 and relocated to [[Buenos Aires]], where he worked as a [[printing]] apprentice in the industrial [[Barracas, Buenos Aires|Barracas]] section of the Argentine capital. Returning to Montevideo in the late 1940s, he developed an interest in [[Afro-Uruguayan]] culture. Settling in Montevideo's primarily black neighbourhood of \"Mediomundo\" (\"Half-World\"), he studied the [[Candombe|Candomb\u00e9]] and [[Comparsa]] dances characteristic to the culture.<ref>[http://www.carlospaezvilaro.com/cpv/home/home/index.php?menu=sub1_2&t=secciones&secc=10257&sub=10260 Artist's bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911192328/http://www.carlospaezvilaro.com/cpv/home/home/index.php?menu=sub1_2&t=secciones&secc=10257&sub=10260 |date=September 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHe composed numerous musical pieces in the two genres and conducted an orchestra. His group's [[conga]]s and [[Bongo drum|bongos]] were decorated with their leader's own thematic drawings, as well. His interest in the culture later led him to [[Brazil]], home to the western hemisphere's largest population of [[Afro-Brazilian|African descent]]. P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 was invited to exhibit some of this work by the Director of the [[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris|Modern Art Museum of Paris]], [[Jean Cassou]], in 1956. He traveled to [[Dakar]], [[Senegal]], later that year - his first visit to Africa.<ref name=lanacion>[http://www.lanacion.com.ar/nota.asp?nota_id=537743 ''La Naci\u00f3n'' {{in lang|es}}]</ref>\n\nHe was one of the \"Grupo de los 8\", a movement of Uruguayan artists formed in 1958 together with Oscar Garc\u00eda Reino, Miguel \u00c1ngel Pareja, Ra\u00fal Pavlovsky, Lincoln Presno, Am\u00e9rico Sposito, Alfredo Testoni and Julio Verdie in order to promote new tendencies in painting. In 1960 they were invited by art critic [[Rafael Squirru]] to join the international exhibition at the [[Buenos Aires Museum of Modern Art]] (of which he was creator and first director) with artists such as [[Willem De Kooning]], [[Roger Hilton]] and [[Lucio Fontana]]. The experimental tendencies of the Grupo de los 8 have since gained a place of unquestionable relevance not only in the panorama of Uruguayan art but also at an international level, some of their works forming part of museums and collections worldwide.\n\nIncreasingly well-known, P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 was commissioned in 1959 to create a mural for a tunnel connecting a new annex to the [[Organization of American States]]' [[Washington, DC]] headquarters, the Pan American Union building. Originally intended to be no more than {{convert|15|m}} in length, the completed mural (''Roots of Peace'') measured {{convert|155|m}} long and nearly {{convert|2|m}} high when unveiled in 1960. Extensive damage from humidity prompted the artist to repaint the mural in 1975.<ref>[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-25153240_ITM Access My Library: The Bright side of the tunnel]</ref>\n[[File:Casapueblo.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Casapueblo Uruguay|Casapueblo]], his \"livable sculpture\" and best-known creation near [[Punta del Este]], has been a leading tourist destination in Uruguay since the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daylife.com/photo/05LG0cT9Bb1XG |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318075236/http://www.daylife.com/photo/05LG0cT9Bb1XG |archivedate=2012-03-18 }}</ref>]] \nHe purchased a sea-front property on eastern Uruguay's scenic, then-desolate [[Punta Ballena]] in 1958, building a small, wooden lodge that over time became \"[[Casapueblo Uruguay|Casapueblo]]\" (\"House-Village\"). The sprawling compound, a whitewashed cement [[citadel]] reminiscent of [[Mykonos]], was built in stages by the artist to resemble the mud nests created by the region's native [[hornero]] birds, and became his home, [[wikt:atelier|atelier]] and museum.<ref name=\"onsc\">[http://www.onsc.gub.uy/gxpsites/Archivos%5CPublicaciones%5CRevistaONSC%5CR34%5C02.%20Museo%20Casapueblo.pdf ONSC: Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 {{in lang|es}}]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> Though he resided in Casapueblo - his \"livable sculpture\" - by 1968, P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 continued to add on to the structure, at times creating a room for a particular guest. He later opened a section of Casapueblo to tourism as a hotel.<ref name=nueve>[http://nueve-franjas-y-un-sol.blogia.com/2006/072501-carlos-paez-vilaro.php Nueve franjas y un sol {{in lang|es}}] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827111044/http://nueve-franjas-y-un-sol.blogia.com/2006/072501-carlos-paez-vilaro.php |date=2009-08-27 }}</ref><ref name=clarin>[http://www.servicios.clarin.com/notas/jsp/enie/v1/notas/imprimir.jsp?pagid=1718013 ''Clar\u00edn'' {{in lang|es}}] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708163040/http://www.servicios.clarin.com/notas/jsp/enie/v1/notas/imprimir.jsp?pagid=1718013 |date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nP\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 remained active in European and African culture, as well. He remained close with numerous friends from his days in [[Paris]] in the late 1950s, particularly [[Brigitte Bardot]] and [[Pablo Picasso]], and in 1967, established a [[film production]] company (\"Dahlia\") with the help of European industrialists Gerard Leclery and [[Gunther Sachs]].<ref>[http://www.magicasruinas.com.ar/revistero/internacional/internacional-casapueblo-paez-vilaro.htm P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3: Un personaje de novela. ''Gente''(20 February 1969) {{in lang|es}}]</ref> He traveled in numerous [[West Africa]]n nations to make a documentary, ''Batouk'', with director Jean-Jacques Manigot and poet [[Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0218026/ imdb: ''Batouk'']</ref> \n\nThe artist's first marriage, to Madel\u00f3n Rodr\u00edguez G\u00f3mez, though brief, produced three children. One of them, [[Carlitos P\u00e1ez|Carlos \"Carlitos\" P\u00e1ez Rodr\u00edguez]], would later join the [[Stella Maris College (Montevideo)|Stella Maris College]] \"Old Christians\" [[Rugby union|Rugby]] team; on 13 October 1972, [[Uruguayan Air Force Flight 571]] carrying the team crashed in the forbidding [[Andes]] range, between [[Chile]] and [[Mendoza Province]], [[Argentina]]. P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 joined the [[search and rescue]] mission for the 45 passengers, of which 16 survived, including his son, with whom he was reunited shortly after their 23 December rescue.<ref>[http://www.viven.com.uy/571/eng/default.asp Viven {{in lang|es}}]</ref> \n\nP\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 experienced difficulties in other areas of his life. He met Annette Deussen, an Argentine tourist, in 1976, and she had his child in 1984. Deussen was married to another man at the time, and the marriage dissolved in 1986; she and P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 married in 1989. Her former spouse, however, continued his legal fight for the child for over a decade, even after P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3's paternity was established by tests.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/1998/10/12/e-03901d.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' (12 October 1998) {{in lang|es}}]</ref> The matter was ultimately resolved in the P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3s' favor in 1999.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/1999/11/07/e-05401d.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' (7 November 1999) {{in lang|es}}]</ref> \n[[File:Works by Carlos P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3.jpg|thumb|210px|A number of recent paintings by the artist, on display at Casapueblo.]]\nHe continued to create murals and sculptures for various government offices, corporate headquarters, private homes, and other buildings. He created 12 murals in [[Argentina]], 16 in [[Brazil]], 4 in [[Chad]], 3 in [[Chile]], 4 in [[Gabon]], 11 in the [[United States]], and 30 in his native [[Uruguay]], as well as a scattering of works elsewhere in [[Africa]] and in the [[Polynesian islands]].<ref name=nueve/> He also designed a non-denominational [[chapel]] for a cemetery without crosses or headstones in [[San Isidro, Buenos Aires]] and rebuilt an abandoned house in nearby [[Tigre, Buenos Aires|Tigre]] in 1989 in the manner of Casapueblo; he considered the San Isidro chapel his \"greatest work\".   In his last years the artist divided his time between Casapueblo and \"Bengala,\" his Tigre residence.<ref name=clarin/>\n\nOn 24 February 2014 P\u00e1ez Vilar\u00f3 died at the age of 90 at his home ''Casapueblo'', in Punta Ballena.\n\nHis son stated in reaction to his father's death \"I hope he rests in peace. I've never seen a guy who works that much, and I mean it. He worked up until yesterday.\"<ref>[http://www.montevideo.com.uy/notnoticias_227353_1.html ''Montevideo Portal'' (24 February 2014) {{in lang|es}}] </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.thegreatcat.org/the-cat-in-art-and-photos-2/cats-in-art-20th-century/carlos-paez-vilaro-1923-2014-uruguayan/ Carlos' cats]\n\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paez Vilaro, Carlos}}\n[[Category:Uruguayan muralists]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan painters]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan potters]]\n[[Category