r />y '''Y'''uan, '''y'''eeast\n|}\n\n====Consonants====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Letter(s)\n! Phoneme(s)\n! Examples\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | b, bb\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/b/}}\n| '''b'''unscoill, '''b'''en\n|-\n| between vowels\n| {{IPA|/\u03b2/}} or {{IPA|/v/}}\n| ca'''bb'''yl\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | c, cc, ck\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/k/}}\n| buns'''c'''oill, '''c'''loan\n|-\n| between vowels\n| {{IPA|/\u0261/}}<br />{{IPA|/\u0263/}}\n| pe'''cc'''ah, ga'''cc'''an<br />feea'''ck'''le, cra'''ck'''an\n|-\n| colspan=2 | ch\n| {{IPA|/x/}}\n| '''ch'''a\n|-\n| colspan=2 | \u00e7h, t\u00e7h\n| {{IPA|/t\u0283/}}\n| '''\u00e7h'''iarn, '''\u00e7h'''engey, pai'''t\u00e7h'''ey\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | d, dd, dh\n| broad\n| {{IPA|/d\u032a/}}\n| keea'''d''', ar'''d'''nieu, te'''dd''', '''dh'''one\n|-\n| slender\n| {{IPA|/d\u02b2/}} or {{IPA|/d\u0292/}}\n| feei'''d'''\n|-\n| broad, between vowels\n| {{IPA|/\u00f0/}}\n| e'''dd'''in, mo'''dd'''ey\n|-\n| colspan=2 | f\n| {{IPA|/f/}}\n| '''f'''ys, '''f'''eeackle\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | g, gg\n| broad\n| {{IPA|/\u0261/}}\n| '''G'''aelg, Ghael'''g'''agh\n|-\n| slender\n| {{IPA|/\u0261\u02b2/}}\n| '''g'''eurey, '''g'''einnagh\n|-\n| between vowels\n| {{IPA|/\u0263/}}\n| ve'''gg'''ey, ru'''gg'''it\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | gh\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/\u0263/}}<br />\u2205\n| '''Gh'''aelgagh, bea'''gh'''ey<br />sha'''gh'''ey\n|-\n| finally or before t\n| {{IPA|/x/}}\n| jeera'''gh''', cla'''gh''', cooina'''gh'''tyn\n|-\n| colspan=2 | -ght\n| {{IPA|/x/}}\n| toshia'''ght''', ho'''ght'''\n|-\n| colspan=2 | h\n| {{IPA|/h/}}\n| '''h'''oght\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | j, dj\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292/}}\n| mooin'''j'''er, '''j'''eeragh\n|-\n| between vowels\n| {{IPA|/\u0292/}}<br />{{IPA|/j/}}\n| pa'''dj'''er<br />mai'''dj'''ey, fe'''dj'''ag\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | k\n| broad\n| {{IPA|/k/}}\n| '''k'''eyl, eair'''k'''\n|-\n| slender\n| {{IPA|/k\u02b2/}}\n| '''k'''ione, '''k'''iare\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | l, ll\n| broad\n| {{IPA|/l/}}\n| Gae'''l'''g, s'''l'''eityn, moy'''ll'''ey\n|-\n| slender\n| {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}}\n| g'''l'''ion, b'''l'''ein, fei'''ll''', bi'''ll'''ey\n|-\n| finally, in monosyllabic words (S only)\n| {{IPA|/\u1d48l/}}\n| shooy'''l'''\n|-\n| colspan=2 | -le\n| {{IPA|/\u0259l/}}\n| feeack'''le'''\n|-\n| colspan=2 | lh\n| {{IPA|/l/}}\n| '''lh'''ong\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | m, mm\n| normally\n| {{IPA|/m/}}\n| '''m'''ooinjer, dreey'''m''', fa'''mm'''an\n|-\n| finally, in monosyllabic words (N only)\n| {{IPA|/\u1d47m/}}\n| eey'''m''', tro'''m'''e\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | n\n| broad\n| {{IPA|/n/}}\n| bu'''n'''scoill, cooinaghty'''n''', e'''nn'''ym\n|-\n| slender\n| {{IPA|/n\u02b2/}}\n| ard'''n'''ieu, colla'''n'''eyn, dooi'''nn'''ey, gei'''nn'''agh\n|-\n| finally, in monosyllabic words\n| {{IPA|/\u1d48n/}}\n| sla'''n'''e, be'''n'''\n|-\n| slender, finally, in monosyllabic words\n| {{IPA|/\u1d48n\u02b2/}}\n| ei'''n'''\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | ng\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/\u014b/}}<br />{{IPA|/n\u02b2/}}\n| y'''ng'''yn<br />che'''ng'''ey\n|-\n| finally, in monosyllabic words (S only)\n| {{IPA|/\u1da2\u014b/}}\n| lho'''ng'''\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | p, pp\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/p/}}\n| '''p'''eccah, '''p'''adjer\n|-\n| between vowels\n| {{IPA|/v/}}\n| ca'''pp'''an\n|-\n| colspan=2 | qu\n| {{IPA|/kw/}}\n| '''qu'''eig\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | r, rr\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/r/}}\n| geu'''r'''ey, jee'''r'''agh, fe'''rr'''ishyn\n|-\n| finally\n| {{IPA|[\u0279\u031d]}} or {{IPA|[\u0259\u032f]}}\n| ae'''r''', faiy'''r'''\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | s, ss\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/s/}}<br />{{IPA|/z/}}\n| bun'''s'''coill, '''s'''leityn, ca'''ss'''<br />fy'''s'''\n|-\n| initially before n\n| {{IPA|/\u0283/}}\n| '''s'''niaghtey\n|-\n| between vowels\n| {{IPA|/\u00f0/}}<br />{{IPA|/z/}}\n| sha'''ss'''oo<br /> poo'''s'''it\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | sh\n| usually\n| {{IPA|/\u0283/}}\n| '''sh'''ooyl, vondei'''sh'''\n|-\n| between vowels\n| {{IPA|/\u0292/}}<br />{{IPA|/j/}}\n| aa'''sh'''agh, u'''sh'''ag <br /> to'''sh'''iaght\n|-\n| colspan=2 | -st\n| {{IPA|/s/}}\n| eay'''st''', eea'''st'''\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | t, tt, th\n| broad\n| {{IPA|/t\u032a/}}\n| '''t'''rome, cooinagh'''t'''yn, '''th'''alloo\n|-\n| slender\n| {{IPA|/t\u02b2/}} or {{IPA|/t\u0283/}}\n| poosi'''t''', ush'''t'''ey, tui'''tt'''ym\n|-\n| broad, between vowels\n| {{IPA|/d\u032a/}}<br />{{IPA|/\u00f0/}}\n| bra'''tt'''ag<br />baa'''t'''ey\n|-\n| slender, between vowels\n| {{IPA|/d\u02b2/}} or {{IPA|/d\u0292/}}\n| slei'''t'''yn\n|-\n| colspan=2 | v\n| {{IPA|/v/}}\n| '''v'''eggey, '''v'''oyllagh\n|-\n| colspan=2 | w\n| {{IPA|/w/}}\n| a'''w'''in\n|}\n\n==Phonology==\n{{IPA notice}}\n\n===Consonants===\nThe consonant phonemes of Manx are as follows:<ref>Thomson 1992, 128\u201329; Broderick 1993, 234</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+Manx consonant phonemes\n|-\n! &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Labiodental consonant|Labio-<br />dental]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Dental consonant|Dental]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Postalveolar consonant|Post-<br />alveolar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Palatalization (phonetics)|Palato-<br />velar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[labialized velar consonant|Labio-<br />velar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! [[Plosive]]\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|p}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|b}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|t\u032a}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|d\u032a}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|t\u02b2}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|d\u02b2}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|k\u02b2}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|\u0261\u02b2}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|k}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|\u0261}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n! [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|f}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|v}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|s}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|\u0283}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|x\u02b2}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|\u0263\u02b2}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|x}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|\u0263}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|h}} || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n! [[Nasal stop|Nasal]]\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|m}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|n}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|n\u02b2}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|\u014b\u02b2}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|\u014b}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n! [[Trill consonant|Trill]]\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|r}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n! [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|j}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|w}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n! [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]]\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|l}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | {{IPA|l\u02b2}}\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"border-right-width: 0;\" | &nbsp; || style=\"border-left-width: 0;\" | &nbsp;\n|}\n\nThe voiceless plosives are pronounced with [[aspiration (phonetics)|aspiration]]. The dental, postalveolar and palato-velar plosives {{IPA|/t\u032a d\u032a t\u02b2 d\u02b2 k\u02b2/}} are [[affrication|affricated]] to {{IPA|[t\u032a\u0361\u03b8 d\u032a\u0361\u00f0 t\u0361\u0283 d\u0361\u0292 k\u0361x\u02b2]}} in many contexts.\n\nManx has an optional process of [[lenition]] of plosives between vowels, whereby voiced plosives and voiceless fricatives become voiced fricatives and voiceless plosives become either voiced plosives or voiced fricatives. This process introduces the [[allophone]]s {{IPA|[\u03b2 \u00f0 z \u0292]}} to the series of voiced fricatives in Manx. The voiced fricative {{IPA|[\u0292]}} may be further lenited to {{IPA|[j]}}, and {{IPA|[\u0263]}} may disappear altogether. Examples include:<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386, 3:3\u201313; Thomson 1992, 129</ref>\n;Voiceless plosive to voiced plosive\n* {{IPA|/t\u032a/}} > {{IPA|[d\u032a]}}: {{lang|gv|brattag}} {{IPA|[\u02c8brad\u032aa\u0261]}} \"flag, rag\"\n* {{IPA|/k/}} > {{IPA|[\u0261]}}: {{lang|gv|peccah}} {{IPA|[\u02c8p\u025b\u0261\u0259]}} \"sin\"\n;Voiceless plosive to voiced fricative\n* {{IPA|/p/}} > {{IPA|[v]}}: {{lang|gv|cappan}} {{IPA|[\u02c8kavan]}} \"cup\"\n* {{IPA|/t\u032a/}} > {{IPA|[\u00f0]}}: {{lang|gv|baatey}} {{IPA|[\u02c8b\u025b\u02d0\u00f0\u0259]}} \"boat\"\n* {{IPA|/k/}} > {{IPA|[\u0263]}}: {{lang|gv|feeackle}} {{IPA|[\u02c8fi\u02d0\u0263\u0259l]}} \"tooth\"\n;Voiced plosive to voiced fricative\n* {{IPA|/b/}} > {{IPA|[v]}}: {{lang|gv|cabbyl}} {{IPA|[\u02c8ka\u02d0v\u0259l]}} \"horse\"\n* {{IPA|/d\u032a/}} > {{IPA|[\u00f0]}}: {{lang|gv|eddin}} {{IPA|[\u02c8\u025b\u00f0\u0259n\u02b2]}} \"face\"\n* {{IPA|/d\u02b2/}} > {{IPA|[\u0292]}}: {{lang|gv|padjer}} {{IPA|[\u02c8pa\u02d0\u0292\u0259r]}} \"prayer\"\n* {{IPA|/d\u02b2/}} > {{IPA|[\u0292]}} > {{IPA|[j]}}: {{lang|gv|maidjey}} {{IPA|[\u02c8ma\u02d0\u0292\u0259], [\u02c8ma\u02d0j\u0259]}} \"stick\"\n* {{IPA|/\u0261/}} > {{IPA|[\u0263]}}: {{lang|gv|ruggit}} {{IPA|[\u02c8ro\u0263\u0259t]}} \"born\"\n;Voiceless fricative to voiced fricative\n* {{IPA|/s/}} > {{IPA|[\u00f0]}} or {{IPA|[z]}}: {{lang|gv|poosit}} {{IPA|[\u02c8pu\u02d0\u00f0it\u02b2] or [\u02c8pu\u02d0zit\u02b2]}} \"married\"\n* {{IPA|/s/}} > {{IPA|[\u00f0]}}: {{lang|gv|shassoo}} {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0283a\u02d0\u00f0u]}} \"stand\"\n* {{IPA|/\u0283/}} > {{IPA|[\u0292]}}: {{lang|gv|aashagh}} {{IPA|[\u02c8\u025b\u02d0\u0292ax]}} \"easy\"\n* {{IPA|/\u0283/}} > {{IPA|[\u0292]}} > {{IPA|[j]}}: {{lang|gv|toshiaght}} {{IPA|[\u02c8t\u032a\u0254\u0292ax], [\u02c8t\u032a\u0254jax]}} \"beginning\"\n* {{IPA|/x/}} > {{IPA|[\u0263]}}: {{lang|gv|beaghey}} {{IPA|[\u02c8b\u025b\u02d0\u0263\u0259]}} \"live\"\n* {{IPA|/x/}} > {{IPA|[\u0263]}} > \u2205: {{lang|gv|shaghey}} {{IPA|[\u0283a\u02d0]}} \"past\"\n\nAnother optional process of Manx phonology is [[pre-occlusion]], the insertion of a very short [[plosive consonant]] before a [[sonorant consonant]]. In Manx, this applies to stressed monosyllabic words (i.e. words one syllable long). The inserted consonant is homorganic with the following sonorant, which means it has the same [[place of articulation]]. Long vowels are often shortened before pre-occluded sounds. Examples include:<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386, 3:28\u201334; 1993, 236</ref>\n* {{IPA|/m/}} > {{IPA|[\u1d47m]}}: {{lang|gv|trome}} {{IPA|/t\u032aro\u02d0m/}} > {{IPA|[t\u032aro\u1d47m]}} \"heavy\"\n* {{IPA|/n/}} > {{IPA|[\u1d48n]}}: {{lang|gv|kione}} {{IPA|/k\u02b2o\u02d0n/}} > {{IPA|[k\u02b2o\u1d48n]}} \"head\"\n* {{IPA|/n\u02b2/}} > {{IPA|[\u1d48n\u02b2]}}: {{lang|gv|ein}} {{IPA|/e\u02d0n\u02b2/}} > {{IPA|[e\u02d0\u1d48n\u02b2], [e\u1d48n\u02b2]}} \"birds\"\n* {{IPA|/\u014b/}} > {{IPA|[\u1da2\u014b]}}: {{lang|gv|lhong}} {{IPA|/lo\u014b/}} > {{IPA|[lo\u1da2\u014b]}} \"ship\"\n* {{IPA|/l/}} > {{IPA|[\u1d48l]}}: {{lang|gv|shooyll}} {{IPA|/\u0283u\u02d0l/}} > {{IPA|[\u0283u\u02d0\u1d48l]}} \"walking\"\n\nThe trill {{IPA|/r/}} is realised as a one- or two-contact flap {{IPA|[\u027e]}} at the beginning of syllable, and as a stronger trill {{IPA|[r]}} when preceded by another consonant in the same syllable. At the end of a syllable, {{IPA|/r/}} can be pronounced either as a strong trill {{IPA|[r]}} or, more frequently, as a weak fricative {{IPA|[\u0279\u031d]}}, which may vocalise to a nonsyllabic {{IPA|[\u0259\u032f]}} or disappear altogether.<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386; 3:17\u201318</ref> This vocalisation may be due to the influence of [[Manx English]], which is itself a [[non-rhotic accent]].<ref>Jackson 1955, 118; Concise Oxford Companion to the English Language, 1998, [http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1O29-ISLEOFMAN.html Isle of Man], retrieved 28 September 2008</ref> Examples of the pronunciation of {{IPA|/r/}} include:\n* {{lang|gv|ribbey}} \"snare\" {{IPA|[\u02c8\u027eib\u0259]}}\n* {{lang|gv|arran}} \"bread\" {{IPA|[\u02c8a\u027ean]}}\n* {{lang|gv|mooar}} \"big\" {{IPA|[mu\u02d0r], [mu\u02d0\u0279\u031d], [mu\u02d0\u0259\u032f], [mu\u02d0]}}\n\n===Vowels===\nThe vowel phonemes of Manx are as follows:<ref>Broderick 1993, 230\u201333</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Manx vowel phonemes\n|-\n! rowspan=2 |\n! colspan=3 | [[Vowel length|Short]]\n! colspan=3 | Long\n|-\n! [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! [[Back vowel|Back]]\n! Front\n! Central\n! Back\n|-\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA|i}}\n|\n| {{IPA|u}}\n| {{IPA|i\u02d0}}\n|\n| {{IPA|u\u02d0}}\n|-\n! [[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPA|e}}\n| {{IPA|\u0259}}\n| {{IPA|o}}\n| {{IPA|e\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u00f8\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|o\u02d0}}\n|-\n! [[Open vowel|Open]]\n| {{IPA|\u00e6}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|\u0254}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e6\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|a\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u0254:}}\n|}\n\nThe status of {{IPA|[\u00e6]}} and {{IPA|[\u00e6\u02d0]}} as separate phonemes is debatable, but is suggested by the allophony of certain words such as {{lang|gv|ta}} \"is\", {{lang|gv|mraane}} \"women\", and so on. An alternative analysis is that Manx has the following system, where the vowels {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} have allophones ranging from {{IPA|[\u025b]/[\u025b\u02d0]}} through {{IPA|[\u00e6]/[\u00e6\u02d0]}} to {{IPA|[a]/[a\u02d0]}}. As with Irish and Scottish Gaelic, there is a large amount of vowel allophony, such as that of {{IPA|/a/, /a\u02d0/}}. This depends mainly on the 'broad' and 'slender' status of the neighbouring consonants:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Manx vowel phonemes and their allophonic variation\n|-\n! Phoneme\n! \"Slender\"\n! \"Broad\"\n|-\n| {{IPA|/i/, /i\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[i], [i\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u026a], [\u026a\u02d0]}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|/e/, /e\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[e]/[e\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b]/[\u025b\u02d0]}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|/a/, /a\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b~\u00e6]/[\u025b\u02d0~\u00e6\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[a]/[a\u02d0]/[\u00f8\u02d0]}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0268]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0259]}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|/\u0259i/}} (Middle Gaelic)\n| {{IPA|[i\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u02d0], [\u026f\u02d0], [\u026a\u02d0]}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|/o/, /o\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[o], [o\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0254], [\u0254\u02d0]}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|/u/, /u\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[u], [u\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00f8~\u028a], [u\u02d0]}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|/u\u0259/}} (Middle Gaelic)\n| {{IPA|[i\u02d0], [y\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u026a\u02d0], [\u026f\u02d0], [u\u02d0]}}\n|}\n\nWhen stressed, {{IPA|/\u0259/}} is realised as {{IPA|[\u00f8]}}.<ref>Broderick 1993, 232\u201333</ref>\n\nManx has a relatively large number of [[diphthong]]s, all of them [[Height-harmonic|falling]]:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Manx diphthongs\n! rowspan=2 colspan=2 |\n! colspan=3           | Second element\n|-\n! {{IPA|/i/}}\n! {{IPA|/u/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n|-\n! rowspan=3 | First <br/>element\n! Close\n| {{IPA|ui}}\n|\n| {{IPA|i\u0259 \u2022 u\u0259}}\n|-\n! Mid\n| {{IPA|ei \u2022 \u0259i \u2022 oi}}\n| {{IPA|eu \u2022 \u0259u}}\n|\n|-\n! Open\n| {{IPA|ai}}\n| {{IPA|au}}\n|\n|}\n\n===Stress===\nStress generally falls on the first syllable of a word in Manx, but in many cases, stress is attracted to a long vowel in the second syllable.<ref>Broderick 1993, 236</ref> Examples include:\n* {{lang|gv|buggane}} {{IPA|/b\u0259\u02c8\u0263\u00e6\u02d0n/}} \"sprite\"\n* {{lang|gv|tarroogh}} {{IPA|/t\u032aa\u02c8ru\u02d0x/}} \"busy\"\n* {{lang|gv|reeoil}} {{IPA|/ri\u02d0\u02c8o\u02d0l/}} \"royal\"\n* {{lang|gv|vondeish}} {{IPA|/von\u02c8d\u032ae\u02d0\u0283/}} \"advantage\"\n\n==Morphology==\n\n=== Initial consonant mutations ===\nLike all modern Celtic languages, Manx shows [[consonant mutation#Celtic languages|initial consonant mutation]]s, which are processes by which the initial consonant of a word is altered according to its [[morphology (linguistics)|morphological]] and/or [[syntax|syntactic]] environment.<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386, 1:7\u201321; 1993, 236\u201339; Thomson 1992, 132\u201335</ref> Manx has two mutations: '''[[lenition]]''' and '''[[eclipsis]]''', found on nouns and verbs in a variety of environments; adjectives can undergo lenition but not eclipsis. In the late spoken language of the 20th century the system was breaking down, with speakers frequently failing to use mutation in environments where it was called for, and occasionally using it in environments where it was not called for.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Initial consonant mutation in Manx\n!Unmutated\n! IPA \n!Lenition!! IPA \n!Eclipsis!! IPA\n|-\n|p\n| {{IPA|/p/}} \n|ph|| {{IPA|/f/}} \n|b|| {{IPA|/b/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\">Not attested in the late spoken language (Broderick 1984\u201386, 3:66)</ref>\n|-\n|t(h)\n| {{IPA|/t\u032a/}} \n|h|| {{IPA|/h/, /x/}}\n|d(h)|| {{IPA|/d\u032a/}}\n|-\n|\u00e7h\n| {{IPA|/t\u02b2/}}~{{IPA|/t\u0255/}}\n|h|| {{IPA|/h/, /x\u02b2/}}\n|j|| {{IPA|/d\u02b2/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" />\n|-\n|c, k\n| {{IPA|/k\u02b2/}} \n|ch|| {{IPA|/x\u02b2/}} \n|g|| {{IPA|/\u0261\u02b2/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" />\n|-\n|c, k\nqu\n| {{IPA|/k/}} {{IPA|/kw/}} \n|ch\nwh\n|| {{IPA|/x/, /h/}} {{IPA|/hw/}} \n|g\ngu\n|| {{IPA|/\u0261/}}\n|-\n|b\nbw\n| {{IPA|/b/}}<br />{{IPA|/bw/}} \n|b\nw\n|| {{IPA|/v/}}<br />{{IPA|/w/}} \n|m\nmw\n|| {{IPA|/m/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" /><br />{{IPA|/mw/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" />\n|-\n|d(h)\n| {{IPA|/d\u032a/}} \n|gh|| {{IPA|/\u0263/, /w/}} \n|n|| {{IPA|/n/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" />\n|-\n|j\n| {{IPA|/d\u02b2/}}~{{IPA|/d\u0291/}}\n|gh, y|| {{IPA|/\u0263\u02b2/, /j/}} \n|n|| {{IPA|/n\u02b2/}}\n|-\n|g\n| {{IPA|/\u0261\u02b2/}} \n|gh, y|| {{IPA|/\u0263\u02b2/, /j/}} \n|ng|| {{IPA|/\u014b/}}?<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" />\n|-\n|m\nmw\n| {{IPA|/m/}}<br />{{IPA|/mw/}} \n|v\nw\n|| {{IPA|/v/}}<br />{{IPA|/w/}} \n| colspan=2 align=center | ''(no change)''\n|-\n|f\nfw\n| {{IPA|/f/}}<br />{{IPA|/fw/}} \n|f\n|| zero<br />{{IPA|/hw/}} \n|v\nw\n|| {{IPA|/v/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" /><br />{{IPA|/w/}}<ref name=\"unatt\" group=\"*\" />\n|-\n|s\nsl\n\nsn\n| {{IPA|/s/}}<br />{{IPA|/sl/}}<br />{{IPA|/sn\u02b2/}} \n|s\nsl\n\nsn\n|| {{IPA|/h/}}<br />{{IPA|/l/}}<br />{{IPA|/n\u02b2/}} \n| colspan=2 align=center | ''(no change)''\n|-\n|sh\n| {{IPA|/\u0282/}} \n|h|| {{IPA|/h/ , /x\u02b2/}} \n| colspan=2 align=center | ''(no change)''\n|}\n\n<references group=\"*\" />\nIn the corpus of the late spoken language, there is also one example of the eclipsis (nasalisation) of {{IPA|/\u0261/}}: the sentence {{lang|gv|Ta mee er '''ng'''eddyn yn eayn}} (\"I have found the lamb\"), where ''ng'' is pronounced {{IPA|/n/}}. However, probably this was a mis-transcription; the verbal noun in this case is not {{lang|gv|geddyn}} \"get, fetch\", but rather {{lang|gv|feddyn}} \"find\".<ref>(Broderick 1984\u201386 2:190, 3:66).</ref>\n\n=== Nouns ===\nManx nouns fall into one of two [[grammatical gender|genders]], masculine or feminine. Nouns are inflected for [[grammatical number|number]]. The [[plural]] is formed in a variety of ways, most commonly by addition of the suffix {{lang|gv|-yn}} {{IPA|[\u0259n]}}, but also by vowel change, changing {{lang|gv|-agh}} {{IPA|[ax]}} to {{lang|gv|-ee}} {{IPA|[i\u02d0]}} or {{lang|gv|-eeghyn}} {{IPA|[i\u02d0\u0259n]}} or by adding other endings. There is usually no inflection for [[grammatical case|case]], except in a minority of nouns that have a distinct genitive singular form, which is formed in various ways. (Most common is the addition of the suffix ''-ey'' {{IPA|[\u0259]}} to feminine nouns.) Historical genitive singulars are often encountered in [[compound (linguistics)|compounds]] even when they are no longer [[productivity (linguistics)|productive]] forms; for example {{lang|gv|thie-ollee}} \"cowhouse\" uses the old genitive of {{lang|gv|ollagh}} \"cattle\".<ref>Thomson 1992, 118\u201319; Broderick 1993, 239\u201340</ref> There are also traces of a dative singular in set phrases such as {{lang|gv|ry-chosh}} \"on foot\", contrasting with nominative {{lang|gv|cass}} and genitive {{lang|gv|coshey}} (cf. {{lang|gv|cullee choshey}} \"footwear\", {{lang|gv|bluckan coshey}} \"football, soccer, rugby\").<ref>{{Cite book|title=First Lessons in Manx|last=Goodwin|first=Edmund|last2=Thomson|first2=Robert|publisher=Yn Cheshaght Ghailckagh|year=1966|page=50}}</ref>\n\n=== Adjectives ===\nCertain adjectives have plural as well as singular forms (through the addition ''-ey'' {{IPA|[\u0259]}}), although the use of the singular adjective with a plural noun is usual. Most adjectives end in ''-agh'' {{IPA|[ax]}} and form their [[comparative]]/[[superlative]] form by replacing this with ''-ee'' {{IPA|[i\u02d0]}}, e.g. ''at\u00e7himagh'' \"terrible\" becomes ''at\u00e7himee'', giving ''ny s'at\u00e7himee'' \"more terrible\" and ''s'at\u00e7himee'' \"most terrible\". As in Irish and Scottish Gaelic, the comparative-superlative is commonly marked by the copula verb ''s'' (''is'') in the present, and ''by'' in the past; the superlative is often shown by the word \"nys\" /nis/, from Middle Irish ''n\u00ed as'' \"thing that is\" (cf. Irish ''n\u00edos'', past ''n\u00ed ba'').<ref>{{Cite book|title=Conversational Manx|last=Gell|first=John|publisher=Yn Cheshaght Ghailckagh|year=1989|isbn=1870029100|location=St. Judes|page=34}}</ref> A number of adjectives form their comparative/superlative irregularly:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Irregular comparative/superlative forms of Manx adjectives\n!Positive\n!English\n!Comparative/Superlative\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|aalin}}\n|beautiful\n|{{lang|gv|aaley}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|aashag}}\n|easy\n|{{lang|gv|assey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|aeg}}\n|young\n|{{lang|gv|aa}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ard}}\n|high\n|{{lang|gv|yrjey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|beg}}\n|small\n|{{lang|gv|loo}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|bog}}\n|soft, moist\n|{{lang|gv|buiggey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|bwaagh}}\n|pretty\n|{{lang|gv|bwaaie}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|\u00e7heh}}\n|hot\n|{{lang|gv|\u00e7hoe}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|\u00e7hionn}}\n|tight, fast\n|{{lang|gv|\u00e7henney}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|\u00e7hiu}}\n|thick\n|{{lang|gv|\u00e7hee}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|faggys}}\n|near\n|{{lang|gv|niessey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|foddey}}\n|far, long\n|{{lang|gv|odjey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|garroo}}\n|rough\n|{{lang|gv|girroo}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|gial}}\n|bright, white\n|{{lang|gv|gilley}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|giare}}\n|short\n|{{lang|gv|girrey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|lajer}}\n|strong\n|{{lang|gv|troshey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|leah}}\n|soon\n|{{lang|gv|leaie}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|lheann}}\n|wide\n|{{lang|gv|lea}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|liauyr}}\n|long, tall\n|{{lang|gv|lhiurey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|mie}}\n|good\n|{{lang|gv|share}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|moal}}\n|slow\n|{{lang|gv|melley}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|mooar}}\n|large, big\n|{{lang|gv|moo}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|olk}}\n|bad, evil\n|{{lang|gv|messey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|reagh}}\n|merry, lively\n|{{lang|gv|reaie}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|roauyr}}\n|fat, broad\n|{{lang|gv|riurey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|shenn}}\n|old\n|{{lang|gv|shinney}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|thanney}}\n|thin\n|{{lang|gv|theinney}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|trome}}\n|heavy\n|{{lang|gv|thrimmey}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ymmodee}}\n|many\n|{{lang|gv|lee}}\n|}\nThe comparative/superlative can also be formed using {{lang|gv|smoo}} \"more\" with the positive form e.g. {{lang|gv|s'thrimmey}} = {{lang|gv|smoo trome}}.\n\n=== Pronouns ===\nIn common with Irish and Scottish Gaelic, in addition to its regular personal pronouns, Manx has also a series used for emphasis. Under certain phonological circumstances, these can be used as unemphatic pronouns, e.g. \"you were not\" is {{lang|gv|cha row uss}} {{IPA|[xa \u02c8rau \u028as]}} as {{lang|gv|cha row oo}} {{IPA|[xa \u02c8rau u(\u02d0)]}} sounds too similar to {{lang|gv|cha row}} {{IPA|[xa \u02c8rau]}} \"they/he/she was not\".\n\nNotice the only difference between the masculine and feminine third person singular possessive pronouns is the [[Consonant mutation|initial sound change]], namely lenition and h-prefixing, they cause, e.g. {{lang|gv|e glioonag}} \"her laptop\", {{lang|gv|e ghlioonag}} \"his laptop\", ''e ooh'' \"his egg\", ''e hooh'' \"her egg\".\n\nAn alternative to using the possessive pronouns is to precede a noun with the definite article and follow it with the inflected form of {{lang|gv|ec}} \"at\" to show the person, e.g. {{lang|gv|yn thie aym}} \"my house\" (literally \"the house at me\") instead of {{lang|gv|my hie}} \"my house\". This is especially useful in the plural, where all persons share one possessive pronoun, e.g. {{lang|gv|yn thie oc}} \"their house\", as opposed to {{lang|gv|nyn dhie}} \"our/your/their house\".\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Manx personal pronouns'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Person\n!Regular\n!Emphatic\n!Possessive\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | First singular\n|{{lang|gv|mee}}\n|{{lang|gv|mish}}\n|{{lang|gv|my}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Second singular\n|{{lang|gv|oo}}\n|{{lang|gv|uss}}\n|{{lang|gv|dty}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Third singular\n!masculine\n|{{lang|gv|eh}}\n|{{lang|gv|eshyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|e}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>\n|-\n!feminine\n|{{lang|gv|ee}}\n|{{lang|gv|ish}}\n|{{lang|gv|e}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | First plural\n|{{lang|gv|shin}}\n|{{lang|gv|shinyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|nyn}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[2]]]</sup>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Second plural\n|{{lang|gv|shiu}}\n|{{lang|gv|shiuish}}\n|{{lang|gv|nyn}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[2]]]</sup>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Third plural\n|{{lang|gv|ad}}\n|{{lang|gv|adsyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|nyn}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[2]]]</sup>\n|}\n\n1.'''[[Template:Ref label|^]]''' Causes lenition.\n\n2.'''[[Template:Ref label|^]]''' Causes eclipsis.\n\n=== Verbs ===\nManx verbs generally form their [[finite verb|finite]] forms by means of [[periphrasis]]: inflected forms of the [[auxiliary verb]]s {{lang|gv|ve}} \"to be\" or {{lang|gv|jannoo}} \"to do\" are combined with the [[verbal noun]] of the main verb. Only the [[future tense|future]], [[conditional tense|conditional]], [[preterite]], and [[imperative mood|imperative]] can be formed directly by inflecting the main verb, but even in these tenses, the periphrastic formation is more common in Late Spoken Manx.<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386, 75\u201382; 1993, 250, 271; Thomson 1992, 122</ref> Examples:\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|+ '''Manx finite verb forms'''\n|-\n! Tense\n! Periphrastic form<br />(literal translation)\n! Inflected form\n! Gloss\n|-\n! Present\n| {{lang|gv|ta mee tilgey}}<br />(I am throwing)\n| \u2013\n| I throw\n|-\n! Imperfect\n| {{lang|gv|va mee tilgey}}<br />(I was throwing)\n| \u2013\n| I was throwing\n|-\n! Perfect\n| {{lang|gv|ta mee er jilgey}}<br />(I am after throwing)<ref name=er>The particle {{lang|gv|er}} is identical in form to the preposition {{lang|gv|er}} \"on\"; however, it is etymologically distinct, coming from Old Irish {{lang|sga|\u00edar}} \"after\" (Williams 1994, 725).</ref>\n| \u2013\n| I have thrown\n|-\n! Pluperfect\n| {{lang|gv|va mee er jilgey}}<br />(I was after throwing)<ref name=er />\n| \u2013\n| I had thrown\n|-\n! Preterite\n| {{lang|gv|ren mee tilgey}}<br />(I did throwing)\n| {{lang|gv|hilg mee}}\n| I threw\n|-\n! Future\n| {{lang|gv|neeym tilgey}}<br />(I will do throwing)\n| {{lang|gv|tilgym}}\n| I will throw\n|-\n! Conditional\n| {{lang|gv|yinnin tilgey}}<br />(I would do throwing)\n| {{lang|gv|hilgin}}\n| I would throw\n|-\n! Imperative\n| {{lang|gv|jean tilgey}}<br />(Do throwing!)\n| {{lang|gv|tilg}}\n| Throw!\n|-\n!Past participle\n|\u2013\n|{{lang|gv|tilgit}}\n|thrown\n|}\n\nThe future and conditional tenses (and in some [[irregular verb]]s, the preterite) make a distinction between [[Dependent and independent verb forms|\"independent\" and \"dependent\" forms]]. Independent forms are used when the verb is not preceded by any particle; dependent forms are used when a particle (e.g. {{lang|gv|cha}} \"not\") does precede the verb. For example, \"you will lose\" is {{lang|gv|caillee oo}} with the independent form {{lang|gv|caillee}} (\"will lose\"), while \"you will not lose\" is {{lang|gv|cha gaill oo}} with the dependent form {{lang|gv|caill}} (which has undergone [[#Initial consonant mutations|eclipsis]] to {{lang|gv|gaill}} after {{lang|gv|cha}}). Similarly \"they went\" is {{lang|gv|hie ad}} with the independent form {{lang|gv|hie}} (\"went\"), while \"they did not go\" is {{lang|gv|cha jagh ad}} with the dependent form {{lang|gv|jagh}}.<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386, 1:92; 1992, 250; Thomson 1992, 122</ref> This contrast is inherited from Old Irish, which shows such pairs as {{lang|sga|beirid}} (\"(s)he carries\") vs. {{lang|sga|n\u00ed beir}} (\"(s)he does not carry\"), and is found in Scottish Gaelic as well, e.g. {{lang|gd|gabhaidh}} (\"will take\") vs. {{lang|gd|cha ghabh}} (\"will not take\"). In Modern Irish, the distinction is found only in irregular verbs (e.g. {{lang|ga|chonaic}} (\"saw\") vs. {{lang|ga|n\u00ed fhaca}} (\"did not see\").\n\nThe fully inflected forms of the regular verb {{lang|gv|tilgey}} \"to throw\" are as follows. In addition to the forms below, a past participle may be formed using {{lang|gv|-it}}: {{lang|gv|tilgit}} \"thrown\".\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Inflection of a regular Manx verb'''\n!Tense\n!Independent\n!Dependent\n!Relative\n|-\n!Preterite\n|{{lang|gv|hilg}}\n|(same as independent)\n|\n|-\n!Future\n|{{lang|gv|tilgym}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>, {{lang|gv|tilgmayd}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[2]]]</sup>, {{lang|gv|tilgee}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[3]]]</sup>\n|{{lang|gv|dilgym<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>, dilgmayd<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[2]]]</sup>, dilgee<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[3]]]</sup>}}\n|{{lang|gv|tilgys}}\n|-\n!Conditional\n|{{lang|gv|tilgin}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>, {{lang|gv|tilgagh}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[3]]]</sup>\n|{{lang|gv|dilgin}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>, {{lang|gv|dilgagh}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[3]]]</sup>\n|\n|-\n!Imperative\n|{{lang|gv|tilg}}\n|(same as independent)\n|\n|}\n1.'''[[template:Ref label|^]]''' First person singular, making the use of a following subject pronoun redundant\n\n2.'''[[template:Ref label|^]]''' First person plural, making the use of a following subject pronoun redundant\n\n3.'''[[template:Ref label|^]]''' Used with all other persons, meaning an accompanying subject must be stated, e.g. {{lang|gv|tilgee eh}} \"he will throw\", {{lang|gv|tilgee ad}} \"they will throw\"\n\nThere are a few peculiarities when a verb begins with a vowel, i.e. the addition of {{lang|gv|d'}} in the preterite and {{lang|gv|n'}} in the future and conditional dependent. Below is the conjugation of {{lang|gv|aase}} \"to grow\".\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Inflection of a regular Manx verb beginning with a vowel'''\n!Tense\n!Independent\n!Dependent\n!Relative\n|-\n!Preterite\n|{{lang|gv|d'aase}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>\n|(same as independent)\n|\n|-\n!Future\n|{{lang|gv|aasym, aasmayd, aasee}}\n|{{lang|gv|n'aasym, n'aasmayd, n'aasee}}\n|{{lang|gv|aasys}}\n|-\n!Conditional\n|{{lang|gv|aasin, aasagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|n'aasin, n'aasagh}}\n|\n|-\n!Imperative\n|{{lang|gv|aase}}\n|(same as independent)\n|\n|}\n1.'''[[Template:Ref label|^]]''' {{lang|gv|d'}}  may also be spelt {{lang|gv|j}} when pronounced {{IPA|/d\u02b2/}} {{IPA|[d\u0292]}} i.e. before a slender vowel, e.g. \"ate\" can be either {{lang|gv|d'ee}} or {{lang|gv|jee}}.\n\nThese peculiarities extend to verbs begins with f, e.g. {{lang|gv|faagail}} \"to leave\".\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Inflection of a regular Manx verb beginning with f'''\n!Tense\n!Independent\n!Dependent\n!Relative\n|-\n!Preterite\n|{{lang|gv|d'aag}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>\n|(same as independent)\n|\n|-\n!Future\n|{{lang|gv|faagym, faagmayd, faagee}}\n|{{lang|gv|vaagym, vaagmayd, vaagee}},\n{{lang|gv|n'aagym, n'aagmayd, n'aagee}}\n|{{lang|gv|aagys}}\n|-\n!Conditional\n|{{lang|gv|aagin, aagagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|vaagin, vaagagh}}, {{lang|gv|n'aagin, n'aagagh}}\n|\n|-\n!Imperative\n|{{lang|gv|faag}}\n|(same as independent)\n|\n|}\n1.'''[[Template:Ref label|^]]''' Again, {{lang|gv|d'}}  may also be spelt {{lang|gv|j}} where appropriate.\n\nA number of verbs are irregular in their inflection. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Inflected forms of irregular Manx verbs\n!Form\n!Preterite indep.\n!Preterite dep.\n!Future indep.\n!Future dep.\n!Conditional indep.\n!Conditional dep.\n!Imperative\n!Past participle\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|\u00e7heet}} (come)\n|{{lang|gv|haink}}\n|{{lang|gv|daink}}\n|{{lang|gv|higgym, higmayd, hig}}\n|{{lang|gv|jiggym, jigmayd, jig}}\n|{{lang|gv|harrin, harragh}}\n|{{lang|gv|darrin, darragh}}\n|{{lang|gv|tar}}\n|\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|clashtyn}} (hear)\n|{{lang|gv|cheayll}}\n|{{lang|gv|geayll}}\n|{{lang|gv|cluinnyn, cluinnee, cluinmayd}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[1]]]</sup>\n|{{lang|gv|gluinnyn, gluinnee, gluinmayd}}\n|{{lang|gv|chluinnin, chluinnagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|gluinnin, gluinnagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|clasht}}\n|{{lang|gv|cluinit}}\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|cur}} (put, give)\n|{{lang|gv|hug}}\n|{{lang|gv|dug}}\n|{{lang|gv|verrym, vermayd, ver}}\n|{{lang|gv|derrym, dermayd, der}}\n|{{lang|gv|verrin, verragh}}\n|{{lang|gv|derrin, derragh}}\n|{{lang|gv|cur}}\n|{{lang|gv|currit}}\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|fakin}} (see)\n|{{lang|gv|honnick}}\n|{{lang|gv|vaik}}\n|{{lang|gv|hee'm, hemayd, hee}}\n|{{lang|gv|vaikym, vaikmyd, vaik}}\n|{{lang|gv|heein, heeagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|vaikin, vaikagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|jeeagh, cur-my-ner}}\n|{{lang|gv|faikinit}}\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|feddyn}} (find),\n{{lang|gv|geddyn}} (get),\n|{{lang|gv|hooar}}\n|{{lang|gv|dooar}}\n|{{lang|gv|yioym, yiowmayd, yiow}}\n|{{lang|gv|voym, vowmayd, vow}}\n|{{lang|gv|yioin, yioghe}}\n|{{lang|gv|voin, voghe}}\n|{{lang|gv|fow}}\n|{{lang|gv|feddinynt}} (found),\n{{lang|gv|geddinynt}}\n\n(given)\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|goll}} (go)\n|{{lang|gv|hie}}\n|{{lang|gv|jagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|hem, hemmayd, hed}}\n|{{lang|gv|jem, jemmayd, jed}}\n|{{lang|gv|raghin, ragh}}\n|(same as indep.)\n|{{lang|gv|gow, immee}}\n|\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|gra}} (say)\n|{{lang|gv|dooyrt}}\n|(same as indep.)\n|{{lang|gv|jirrym, jirmayd, jir}}, {{lang|gv|abbyrym, abbyrmyd, abbyr}}\n|{{lang|gv|jirrym, jirmayd, jir}},\n{{lang|gv|niarrym, niarmayd, niar}}, {{lang|gv|n'abbyrym, n'abbyrmyd, n'abbyr}}\n|{{lang|gv|yiarrin, yiarragh}}\n|{{lang|gv|niarrin, niarragh}}\n|{{lang|gv|abbyr}}\n|{{lang|gv|grait}}\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|goaill}} (take)\n|{{lang|gv|ghow}}\n|(same as indep.)\n|{{lang|gv|goym, gowmayd, gowee}}<sup>[[Template:Ref label|[2]]]</sup>\n|{{lang|gv|goym, gowmayd, gow}}\n|{{lang|gv|ghoin, ghoghe}}\n|{{lang|gv|goin, goghe}}\n|{{lang|gv|gow}}\n|{{lang|gv|goit}}\n|-\n!{{lang|gv|jean}} (do)\n|{{lang|gv|ren}}\n|(same as indep.)\n|{{lang|gv|nee'm, neemayd, nee}}\n|{{lang|gv|jeanym, jeanmayd, jean}}\n|{{lang|gv|yinnin, yinnagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|jinnin, jinnagh}}\n|{{lang|gv|jean}}\n|{{lang|gv|jeant}}\n|}\n1.'''[[Template:Ref label|^]]''' Future relative: {{lang|gv|clinnys}}\n2.'''[[Template:Ref label|^]]''' Future relative: {{lang|gv|gowee}}\n\nThe most common and most irregular verb in Manx is {{lang|gv|ve}} \"to be\", often used as an auxiliary verb. In addition to the usual inflected tenses, {{lang|gv|ve}} also has a present tense. The full conjugation of {{lang|gv|ve}} \"to be\" is as follows.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|+ Forms of verb {{lang|gv|ve}} \"to be\"\n|-\n! Form\n! Independent\n! Dependent\n!Relative\n|-\n! Present\n| {{lang|gv|ta}}\n| {{lang|gv|vel, nel}}\n|\u2013\n|-\n!Preterite\n|{{lang|gv|va}}\n|{{lang|gv|row}}\n|\u2013\n|-\n! Future\n| {{lang|gv|bee'm, beemayd, bee}}\n| (same as independent)\n|vees\n|-\n! Conditional\n|{{lang|gv|veign, veagh}}\n| {{lang|gv|beign, beagh}}\n|\u2013\n|-\n!Imperative\n|{{lang|gv|bee}}\n|(same as independent)\n|\u2013\n|}\n\n=== Adverbs ===\nManx adverbs can be formed from adjectives by means of the word {{lang|gv|dy}} (< Middle Irish ''go'' \"with, until\"), e.g. {{lang|gv|mie}} \"good\", {{lang|gv|dy mie}} \"well\" (CF. Irish ''maith'', ''go maith'', Gaelic ''math'', ''gu maith'');  {{lang|gv|gennal}} \"cheerful\", {{lang|gv|dy gennal}} \"cheerfully\". This {{lang|gv|dy}} is not used when preceded by such words as {{lang|gv|ro}} \"too\" and {{lang|gv|feer}} \"very\" or followed by {{lang|gv|dy liooar}} \"enough\", e.g. {{lang|gv|feer vie}} \"very good, very well\", {{lang|gv|gennal dy liooar}} \"cheerful(ly) enough\". The prepositional phrase for \"home(wards)\" is formed with {{lang|gv|dy}} \"to\" and the noun {{lang|gv|balley}} \"place, town, homestead\" to give {{lang|gv|dy valley}}, Cf. Irish ''abhaile'', older ''do bhaile'', whereas the noun {{lang|gv|thie}} \"house, home\" can be used unchanged to convey the same meaning.\n\nThe language has a number of adverbs corresponding to English \"up\" and \"down\", the meaning of which depend upon such things as motion or lack thereof and starting point in relation to the speaker.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Manx adverbs expressing \"up\" and \"down\"\n|-\n! \n! above the speaker\n! below the speaker\n|-\n! Stationary\n| {{lang|gv|heose}} {{IPA|/ho\u02d0s/}}\n| {{lang|gv|heese}} {{IPA|/hi\u02d0s/}}\n|-\n!Movement towards the speaker from\n|{{lang|gv|neose}} {{IPA|/no\u02d0s/}}\n|{{lang|gv|neese}} {{IPA|/ni\u02d0s/}}\n|-\n! Movement away from the speaker to\n|{{lang|gv|seose}} {{IPA|/so\u02d0s/}}\n|{{lang|gv|sheese}} {{IPA|/\u0283i\u02d0s/}}\n|}\nExamples of practical usage are {{lang|gv|Ta dooinney heese y traid}} \"There's a man down the street\" and {{lang|gv|Ta mee goll sheese y traid}} \"I'm going down the street\", {{lang|gv|Jean drappal neese}} \"Climb up (towards me)\" and {{lang|gv|Jean drappal seose}} \"Climb up (away from me)\".\n\n=== Prepositions ===\nLike the other [[Insular Celtic languages]], Manx has so-called [[inflected preposition]]s, contractions of a [[preposition]] with a [[pronoun|pronominal]] direct object, as the following common prepositions show. Note the sometimes identical form of the uninflected preposition and its third person singular masculine inflected form.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Conjugation of Manx prepositions using pronominal ending\n! colspan=\"2\" |Person\n!{{lang|gv|ass}}<br />\"out of\"\n!{{lang|gv|ayns}}<br />\"in\"\n!{{lang|gv|da}}<br />\"to\"\n!{{lang|gv|ec}}<br />\"at\"\n!{{lang|gv|er}}<br />\"on\"\n!{{lang|gv|fo}}<br />\"under\"\n!{{lang|gv|gys}}<br />\"to\"\n!{{lang|gv|jeh}}<br />\"of\"\n!{{lang|gv|lesh}}<br />\"with\"\n!{{lang|gv|marish}}<br />\"with\"\n!{{lang|gv|rish}}<br />\"to\"\n!{{lang|gv|roish}}<br />\"before\"\n!{{lang|gv|veih, voish}}<br />\"from\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |First singular\n|{{lang|gv|assym}}\n|{{lang|gv|aynym}}\n|{{lang|gv|dou}}\n|{{lang|gv|aym}}\n|{{lang|gv|orrym}}\n|{{lang|gv|foym}}\n|{{lang|gv|hym}}\n|{{lang|gv|jeem}}\n|{{lang|gv|lhiam}}\n|{{lang|gv|marym}}\n|{{lang|gv|rhym}}\n|{{lang|gv|roym}}\n|{{lang|gv|voym}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second singular\n|{{lang|gv|assyd}}\n|{{lang|gv|aynyd}}\n|{{lang|gv|dhyt}}\n|{{lang|gv|ayd}}\n|{{lang|gv|ort}}\n|{{lang|gv|foyd}}\n|{{lang|gv|hood}}\n|{{lang|gv|jeed}}\n|{{lang|gv|lhiat}}\n|{{lang|gv|mayrt}}\n|{{lang|gv|rhyt}}\n|{{lang|gv|royd}}\n|{{lang|gv|voyd}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Third singular\n!Masculine\n|{{lang|gv|ass}}\n|{{lang|gv|ayn}}\n|{{lang|gv|da}}\n|{{lang|gv|echey}}\n|{{lang|gv|er}}\n|{{lang|gv|fo}}\n|{{lang|gv|huggey}}\n|{{lang|gv|jeh}}\n|{{lang|gv|lesh}}\n|{{lang|gv|marish}}\n|{{lang|gv|rish}}\n|{{lang|gv|roish}}\n|{{lang|gv|voish, veih}}\n|-\n!Feminine\n|{{lang|gv|assjee}}\n|{{lang|gv|aynjee}}\n|{{lang|gv|jee}}\n|{{lang|gv|eck}}\n|{{lang|gv|urree}}\n|{{lang|gv|foee}}\n|{{lang|gv|huic(k)}}\n|{{lang|gv|j'ee}}\n|{{lang|gv|lhee}}\n|{{lang|gv|maree}}\n|{{lang|gv|r'ee}}\n|{{lang|gv|roee, rhymbee}}\n|{{lang|gv|voee}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |First plural\n|{{lang|gv|assdooin}}\n|{{lang|gv|ayn(dooin)}}\n|{{lang|gv|dooin}}\n|{{lang|gv|ain}}\n|{{lang|gv|orrin}}\n|{{lang|gv|foin}}\n|{{lang|gv|hooin}}\n|{{lang|gv|jin}}\n|{{lang|gv|lhien}}\n|{{lang|gv|marin}}\n|{{lang|gv|rooin}}\n|{{lang|gv|roin}}\n|{{lang|gv|voin}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second plural\n|{{lang|gv|assdiu}}\n|{{lang|gv|ayndiu}}\n|{{lang|gv|diu}}\n|{{lang|gv|eu}}\n|{{lang|gv|erriu}}\n|{{lang|gv|feue}}\n|{{lang|gv|hiu}}\n|{{lang|gv|jiu}}\n|{{lang|gv|lhiu}}\n|{{lang|gv|meriu}}\n|{{lang|gv|riu}}\n|{{lang|gv|reue}}\n|{{lang|gv|veue}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third plural\n|{{lang|gv|assdoo, assdaue}}\n|{{lang|gv|ayndoo, ayndaue}}\n|{{lang|gv|daue}}\n|{{lang|gv|oc}}\n|{{lang|gv|orroo}}\n|{{lang|gv|foue}}\n|{{lang|gv|huc}}\n|{{lang|gv|jeu}}\n|{{lang|gv|lhieu}}\n|{{lang|gv|maroo}}\n|{{lang|gv|roo}}\n|{{lang|gv|roue, rhymboo}}\n|{{lang|gv|voue}}\n|}\nIn addition to the above \"simple\" prepositions, Manx has a number of prepositional phrases based on a noun; being based on nouns, the possessive personal pronouns are used to refer to what would in English be pronominal prepositional objects. This also happens in English phrases such as \"for my sake\".\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Conjugation of Manx prepositional phrases using possessive pronouns\n! colspan=\"2\" |Person\n!{{lang|gv|erskyn}}<br />\"above\"\n!{{lang|gv|mychione}}<br />\"concerning\"\n!{{lang|gv|son}}<br />\"for the sake of\"\n!{{lang|gv|lurg}}<br />\"after\"\n!{{lang|gv|noi}}<br />\"against\"\n!width=300pt|{{lang|gv|trooid}}<br />\"through\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |From Middle Irish\n!''for os ciond''<br>'on/at over head'\n!''um chiond''<br>'about/around head'\n!''ar son''<br>'on/for sake'\n!''lorg''<br>'track, trail, trace'\n!''in aghaidh''<br>'in face DAT'\n!A Northern Gaelic nominalisation of the Middle Irish 3rd person singular preposition *''tromhaid'' 'through him/it', originally found as the article form, cf. Irish ''tr\u00edd an'' 'through the')\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |First singular\n|{{lang|gv|er-my-skyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|my-my-chione}}\n|{{lang|gv|er-my-hon}}\n|{{lang|gv|my lurg}}\n|{{lang|gv|m'oi}}\n|{{lang|gv|my hrooid}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second singular\n|{{lang|gv|er-dty-skyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|my-dty-chione}}\n|{{lang|gv|er-dty-hon}}\n|{{lang|gv|dty lurg}}\n|{{lang|gv|dt'oi}}\n|{{lang|gv|dty hrooid}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Third singular\n!Masculine\n|{{lang|gv|er-e-skyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|my-e-chione}}\n|{{lang|gv|er-e-hon}}\n|{{lang|gv|e lurg}}\n|{{lang|gv|n'oi}}\n|{{lang|gv|e hrooid}}\n|-\n!Feminine\n|{{lang|gv|er-e-skyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|my-e-kione}}\n|{{lang|gv|er-e-son}}\n|{{lang|gv|e lurg}}\n|{{lang|gv|ny hoi}}\n|{{lang|gv|e trooid}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Plural\n|{{lang|gv|er-nyn-skyn}}\n|{{lang|gv|my-nyn-gione}}\n|{{lang|gv|er-nyn-son}}\n|{{lang|gv|nyn lurg}}\n|{{lang|gv|nyn oi}}\n|{{lang|gv|nyn drooid}}\n|}\nAlternative conjugation patterns are sometimes found with these more complex prepositions using inflected prepositions, e.g. {{lang|gv|mychione aym}} for {{lang|gv|my-my-chione}} \"concerning me\", {{lang|gv|son ain}} \"for our sake\" instead of {{lang|gv|er-nyn-son}} \"for our/your/their sake\".\n\n===Numbers===\n{|cellspacing=\"7\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Manx\n! [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]<ref name=Brodvol2 />\n! [[English language|English]]\n! [[Irish language|Irish]]<br />cognate\n! [[Scottish Gaelic]]<br />cognate\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|un<br />nane}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00e6\u02d0n], [o\u02d0n], [u\u02d0n]<br />[ne\u02d0n]}}\n| one\n| {{lang|ga|aon}} {{IPA|[e\u02d0n], [i\u02d0n], [\u026f\u02d0n]}}\n| {{lang|gd|aon}} {{IPA-gd|\u026f\u02d0n|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|daa, ghaa<br />jees}}\n| {{IPA|[d\u032a\u00e6\u02d0]. [\u0263\u00e6\u02d0]<br />[d\u0292i\u02d0s]}}\n| two\n| {{lang|ga|d\u00f3}} {{IPA|[d\u032a\u02e0o\u02d0]}}, ''dh\u00e1/d\u00e1'' {{IPA|[\u0263a\u02d0]/[d\u032a\u02e0a\u02d0]}}<br />(people only) ''d\u00eds'' {{IPA|[d\u02b2i\u02d0\u0283]|}}\n| {{lang|gd|d\u00e0}} {{IPA-gd|t\u032aa\u02d0|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|tree}}\n| {{IPA|[t\u032ari\u02d0]}}\n| three\n| {{lang|ga|tr\u00ed}} {{IPA|[t\u032a\u02b2r\u02b2i\u02d0]}}\n| {{lang|gd|tr\u00ec}} {{IPA-gd|t\u032a\u02b0\u027ei\u02d0|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|kiare}}\n| {{IPA|[k\u02b2\u00e6\u02d0\u0259(r)]}}\n| four\n| {{lang|ga|ceathair}}, {{lang|ga|ceithre}} {{IPA|[cah\u026ar\u02b2], [cer\u02b2h\u02b2\u026a]}}\n| {{lang|gd|ceithir}} {{IPA-gd|\u02c8k\u02b2\u02b0eh\u026a\u027e\u02b2|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|queig}}\n| {{IPA|[kwe\u0261]}}\n| five\n| {{lang|ga|c\u00faig}} {{IPA|[ku\u02d0\u025f]}}\n| {{lang|gd|c\u00f2ig}} {{IPA-gd|k\u02b0o\u02d0k\u02b2|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|shey}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0283e\u02d0]}}\n| six\n| {{lang|ga|s\u00e9}} {{IPA|[\u0283e\u02d0]}}\n| {{lang|gd|sia}} {{IPA-gd|\u0283i\u0259|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|shiaght}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0283\u00e6\u02d0x]}}\n| seven\n| {{lang|ga|seacht}} {{IPA|[\u0283axt]}}\n| {{lang|gd|seachd}} {{IPA-gd|\u0283\u025bxk|}}, {{IPA-gd|\u0283axk|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|hoght}}\n| {{IPA|[ho\u02d0x]}}\n| eight\n| {{lang|ga|ocht}} {{IPA|[oxt]}} (dialect ''hocht'' {{IPA|[hoxt]}})\n| {{lang|gd|ochd}} {{IPA-gd|\u0254xk|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|nuy}}\n| {{IPA|[n\u025bi], [n\u00f8i], [ni\u02d0]}}\n| nine\n| {{lang|ga|naoi}} {{IPA|[n\u02e0e\u02d0], [n\u02e0i\u02d0], [n\u02e0\u0259i]}}\n| {{lang|gd|naoi}} {{IPA-gd|n\u032a\u02e0\u0264i|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|jeih}}\n| {{IPA|[d\u0292\u025bi]}}\n| ten\n| {{lang|ga|deich}} {{IPA|[d\u02b2eh]}}, {{IPA|[d\u0292e\u00e7]}}, {{IPA|[d\u0292ei]}}\n| {{lang|gd|deich}} {{IPA-gd|t\u02b2e\u00e7|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|nane jeig}}\n| {{IPA|[ne\u02d0n d\u0292e\u0261]}}\n| eleven\n| {{lang|ga|aon d\u00e9ag}} {{IPA|[e\u02d0n d\u02b2ia\u0261], [i\u02d0n d\u02b2e\u02d0\u0261], [i\u02d0n/\u026f\u02d0n d\u0292e\u02d0\u0261]}}\n| {{lang|gd|aon deug/diag}} {{IPA-gd|\u026f\u02d0n d\u02b2e:k|}}, {{IPA-gd|\u026f\u02d0n d\u02b2i\u0259k|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|daa yeig}}\n| {{IPA|[d\u032aei\u0261\u02b2]}}\n| twelve\n| {{lang|ga|d\u00f3 dh\u00e9ag}}, {{lang|ga|dh\u00e1 dh\u00e9ag}}, {{lang|ga|d\u00e1 dh\u00e9ag}} {{IPA|[d\u032a\u02e0o\u02d0 jia\u0261], [d\u032a\u02e0o\u02d0 je\u02d0\u0261], [\u0263a\u02d0 je\u02d0\u0261], [d\u032a\u02e0a\u02d0 je\u02d0\u0261]}}\n| {{lang|gd|d\u00e0 dheug/dhiag}} {{IPA-gd|t\u032aa\u02d0 \u029de:k|}}, {{IPA-gd|t\u032aa\u02d0 \u029di\u0259k|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|tree jeig}}\n| {{IPA|[t\u032ari d\u0292e\u0261]}}\n| thirteen\n| {{lang|ga|tr\u00ed d\u00e9ag}} {{IPA|[t\u032a\u02b2r\u02b2i\u02d0 d\u02b2ia\u0261], [t\u032a\u02b2r\u02b2i\u02d0 d\u02b2e\u02d0\u0261], [t\u032a\u02b2r\u02b2i\u02d0 d\u0292e\u02d0\u0261]}}\n| {{lang|gd|tr\u00ec deug/diag}} {{IPA-gd|t\u032a\u02b0\u027ei\u02d0 t\u02b2e:k|}}, {{IPA-gd|t\u032a\u02b0\u027ei\u02d0 t\u02b2i\u0259k|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|feed}}\n| {{IPA|[fi\u02d0d\u0292]}}\n| twenty\n| {{lang|ga|fiche}} {{IPA|[f\u02b2\u026ah\u02b2\u026a], [f\u02b2\u026a\u00e7\u0259]}}; ''fichid'' {{IPA|[f\u02b2\u026ah\u02b2\u026ad\u02b2]}}, {{IPA|[f\u02b2\u026a\u00e7\u026ad\u0292]}} (dative)\n| {{lang|gd|fichead}} {{IPA-gd|fi\u00e7\u0259t\u032a|}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|keead}}\n| {{IPA|[ki\u02d0\u0259d]}}\n| hundred\n| {{lang|ga|c\u00e9ad}} {{IPA|[ce\u02d0d]}}, {{IPA|[ciad]}}\n| {{lang|gd|ceud, ciad}} {{IPA-gd|k\u02b2\u02b0e:t\u032a|}}, {{IPA-gd|k\u02b2\u02b0i\u0259t\u032a|}}\n|}\n\n==Syntax==\nLike most Insular Celtic languages, Manx uses [[verb\u2013subject\u2013object]] word order: the inflected verb of a sentence precedes the [[subject (grammar)|subject]], which itself precedes the [[direct object]].<ref>Broderick 1993, 276</ref> However, as noted above, most finite verbs are formed periphrastically, using an auxiliary verb in conjunction with the verbal noun. In this case, only the auxiliary verb precedes the subject, while the verbal noun comes after the subject. The auxiliary verb may be a [[modal verb]] rather than a form of {{lang|gv|bee}} (\"be\") or {{lang|gv|jannoo}} (\"do\"). Particles like the negative {{lang|gv|cha}} (\"not\") precede the inflected verb. Examples:\n\n<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">\n{|\n| {{sm|main<br />verb}}\n| colspan=2 | {{sm|subject}}\n| colspan=2 | {{sm|direct<br />object}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|Hug}} || {{lang|gv|yn}} || {{lang|gv|saggyrt}} || {{lang|gv|e}} || {{lang|gv|laue}} || {{lang|gv|urree.}}\n|-\n| put-{{sc|pret}} || the || priest || his || hand || on her\n|-\n| colspan=6 | \"The priest put his hand on her.\"<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386, 1:181</ref>\n|}\n&nbsp;\n{|\n| {{sm|aux.<br />verb}}\n| colspan=2 | {{sm|subject}}\n| {{sm|main<br />verb}}\n| colspan=2 | {{sm|direct<br />object}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|Va}} || {{lang|gv|ny}} || {{lang|gv|eayin}} || {{lang|gv|gee}} || {{lang|gv|yn}} || {{lang|gv|conney.}}\n|-\n| were || the || lambs || eat-{{sc|v.n.}} || the || gorse\n|-\n| colspan=6 | \"The lambs used to eat the gorse.\"<ref>Broderick 1984\u201386, 1:179</ref>\n|}\n&nbsp;\n{|\n|  || {{sm|modal<br />verb}} || {{sm|subject}} || {{sm|main<br />verb}} || {{sm|direct<br />object}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|Cha}} || {{lang|gv|jarg}} || {{lang|gv|shiu}} || {{lang|gv|fakin}} || {{lang|gv|red erbee.}}\n|-\n| not || can || you-{{sc|pl}} || see-{{sc|v.n.}} || anything\n|-\n| colspan=5 | \"You can't see anything.\"<ref>Broderick 1993, 274</ref>\n|}\n</div>\n\nWhen the auxiliary verb is a form of {{lang|gv|jannoo}} (\"do\"), the direct object precedes the verbal noun and is connected to it with the particle {{lang|gv|y}}:\n\n<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">\n{|\n| {{sm|aux.<br />verb}} || {{sm|subject}}\n| colspan=2 | {{sm|direct<br />object}}\n|  || {{sm|main<br />verb}}\n|-\n| {{lang|gv|Ren}} || {{lang|gv|ad}} || {{lang|gv|my}} || {{lang|gv|choraa}} || {{lang|gv|y}} || {{lang|gv|chlashtyn.}}\n|-\n| did || they || my || voice || {{sc|particle}} || hear-{{sc|v.n.}}\n|-\n| colspan=6 | \"They heard my voice.\"<ref name=\"Thoms105\"/>\n|}\n</div>\n\nAs in Irish (cf. [[Irish syntax#The forms meaning \"to be\"]]), there are two ways of expressing \"to be\" in Manx: with the substantive verb {{lang|gv|bee}}, and with the copula. The substantive verb is used when the [[predicate (grammar)|predicate]] is an adjective, adverb, or [[prepositional phrase]].<ref>Broderick 1993, 276\u201377</ref> Examples:\n\n<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|t'}} || {{lang|gv|eh}} || {{lang|gv|agglagh}}\n|-\n| is || it || awful/frightening\n|-\n| colspan=3 | \"It is awful/frightening.\"\n|}\n&nbsp;\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|t'}} || {{lang|gv|eh}} || {{lang|gv|dy mie}}\n|-\n| is || he || well\n|-\n| colspan=3 | \"He is well\"\n|}\n&nbsp;\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|t'}} || {{lang|gv|eh}} || {{lang|gv|ayns}} || {{lang|gv|y}} || {{lang|gv|thie-oast}}\n|-\n| is || he || in || the || house-ale ([[pub]])\n|-\n| colspan=5 | \"He is in the ale-house ([[pub]]).\"\n|}\n</div>\n\nWhere the predicate is a noun, it must be converted to a prepositional phrase headed by the preposition {{lang|gv|in}} (\"in\") + possessive pronoun (agreeing with the subject) in order for the substantive verb to be grammatical:\n\n<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|t'}} || {{lang|gv|eh}} || {{lang|gv|ny}} || {{lang|gv|wooinney}} || {{lang|gv|mie}}\n|-\n| is || he || in-his || man || good\n|-\n| colspan=5 | \"He is a good man\" (lit. \"He is in his good man\")<ref>Broderick 1993, 277</ref>\n|}\n</div>\n\nOtherwise, the copula is used when the predicate is a noun. The copula itself takes the form {{lang|gv|is}} or {{lang|gv|she}} in the present tense, but it is often omitted in affirmative statements:\n\n<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|She}} || {{lang|gv|Manninagh}} || {{lang|gv|mish}}\n|-\n| {{sc|copula}} || Manxman || me\n|-\n| colspan=3 | \"I am a Manxman.\"<ref>Broderick 1993, 278</ref>\n|}\n&nbsp;\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|Shoh}} || {{lang|gv|'n}} || {{lang|gv|dooinney}}\n|-\n| this || the || man\n| colspan=3 | \"This is the man.\"<ref name=Thoms105>Thomson 1992, 105</ref>\n|}\n</div>\n\nIn questions and negative sentences, the present tense of the copula is {{lang|gv|nee}}:\n\n<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|Cha}} || {{lang|gv|nee}} || {{lang|gv|mish}} || {{lang|gv|eh}}\n|-\n| not || {{sc|copula}} || me || him\n|-\n| colspan=4 | \"I am not him.\"<ref name=Thoms105 />\n|}\n&nbsp;\n{|\n| {{lang|gv|Nee}} || {{lang|gv|shoh}} || {{lang|gv|'n}} || {{lang|gv|lioar?}}\n|-\n| {{sc|copula}} || this || the || book\n|-\n| colspan=4 | \"Is this the book?\"<ref name=Thoms105 />\n|}\n</div>\n\n==Vocabulary==\nManx vocabulary is predominantly of Goidelic origin, derived from Old Irish and closely related to words in Irish and Scottish Gaelic. However, Manx itself, as well as the languages from which it is derived, borrowed words from other languages as well, especially [[Latin]], [[Old Norse]], [[French language|French]] (particularly [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-Norman]]), and English (both [[Middle English]] and Modern English).<ref>Broderick 1993, 282\u201383</ref>\n\nThe following table shows a selection of nouns from the [[Swadesh list]] and indicates their pronunciations and etymologies.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Manx\n!IPA<ref name=Brodvol2>Broderick 1984\u201386, vol. 2</ref>\n!English\n!Etymology<ref>Macbain 1911; ''Dictionary of the Irish Language''; Broderick 1984\u201386, vol. 2</ref>\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|aane}}\n|{{IPA|[e\u02d0n]}}\n|liver\n|Goidelic; from Mid.Ir. {{lang|mga|ae}} < O.Ir. {{lang|sga|\u00f3a}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|ae}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|adha}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|aer}}\n|{{IPA|[e\u02d0\u0259]}}\n|sky\n|Latin; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|aer}} < L. {{lang|la|a\u00ebr}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|aer}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|adhar}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|aile}}\n|{{IPA|[ail]}}\n|fire\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|aingel}} \"very bright\"; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|aingeal}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ardnieu}}\n|{{IPA|[\u0259rd\u032a\u02c8n\u02b2eu]}}\n|snake\n|Apparently \"highly poisonous\" (cf. {{lang|gv|ard}} \"high\", {{lang|gv|nieu}} \"poison\")\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|awin}}\n|{{IPA|[aun\u02b2], [\u02c8aw\u0259n\u02b2]}}\n|river\n|Goidelic; from the M.Ir. dative form ''abainn'' of {{lang|mga|aba}} < O.Ir. ''abaind'' {{lang|sga|aba}}; cf. Ir. ''abha''/''abhainn'', dative ''abhainn'', Sc.G. {{lang|gd|abhainn}} (literary nominative ''abha'').\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ayr}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8\u00e6\u02d0ar]}}\n|father\n|Goidelic; from M.Ir. ''athair'', O.Ir. {{lang|sga|athir}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|athair}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|beeal}}\n|{{IPA|[bi\u0259l]}}\n|mouth\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|b\u00e9l}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|b\u00e9al}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|beul}}/{{lang|gd|bial}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|beishteig}}\n|{{IPA|[be\u02c8\u0283t\u02b2e\u02d0\u0261], [pr\u0259\u02c8\u0283t\u02b2e\u02d0\u0261]}}\n|worm\n|Latin; from M.Ir. {{lang|mga|piast}}, {{lang|mga|p\u00e9ist}} < O.Ir. {{lang|sga|b\u00edast}} < L. {{lang|la|b\u0113stia}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ben}}\n|{{IPA|[be\u1d48n]}}\n|woman\n|Goidelic; from M.Ir and O.Ir. {{lang|sga|ben}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|bean}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|billey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8bil\u02b2\u0259]}}\n|tree\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|bile}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|blaa}}\n|{{IPA|[bl\u00e6\u02d0]}}\n|flower\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|bl\u00e1th}}, Ir. ''bl\u00e1th'', Sc.G. ''bl\u00e0th''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|blein}}\n|{{IPA|[bl\u02b2e\u02d0n\u02b2], [bl\u02b2i\u1d48n]}}\n|year\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|bliadain}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|blian}}, dat. {{lang|ga|bliain}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|bliadhna}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|bodjal}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8ba\u02d0d\u0292\u0259l]}}\n|cloud\n|English/French; shortened from {{lang|gv|bodjal niaul}} \"pillar of cloud\" (cf. Sc.G. {{lang|gd|baideal ne\u00f2il}}); {{lang|gv|bodjal}} originally meant \"pillar\" or \"battlement\" < E. ''battle'' < Fr. {{lang|fr|bataille}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|bolg}}\n|{{IPA|[bol\u0261]}}\n|belly, bag\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|bolg}}, Ir., Sc.G ''bolg''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|cass}}\n|{{IPA|[ka\u02d0s]}}\n|foot\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|cos}}, cf. Sc.G. {{lang|gd|cas}}, Ir.dialect ''cas'', Ir. ''cos''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|\u00e7hengey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8t\u0283in\u02b2\u0259]}}\n|tongue\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|tengae}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|teanga}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|clagh}}\n|{{IPA|[kla\u02d0x]}}\n|stone\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|cloch}}; cf. Sc.G. {{lang|gd|clach}}, Ir. ''cloch''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|cleaysh}}\n|{{IPA|[kle\u02d0\u0283]}}\n|ear\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. dative {{lang|sga|cl\u00faais}} \"hearing\"; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|cluas}}, dative  {{lang|gd|cluais}}, Ir. dialect ''cluais''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|collaneyn}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8kalin\u02b2\u0259n]}}\n|guts\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|c\u00e1el\u00e1n}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|caol\u00e1n}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|caolan}}, derived from ''caol'' \"thin, slender\", ''-\u00e1n'' nominaliser \n|-\n|{{lang|gv|crackan}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8kra\u02d0\u0263\u0259n]}}\n|skin\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|croiccenn}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|craiceann}}, dialect ''croiceann''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|craue}}\n|{{IPA|[kr\u00e6\u02d0w]}}\n|bone\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|cn\u00e1m}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|cn\u00e1mh}}, dative {{lang|ga|cn\u00e1imh}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|cn\u00e0imh}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|cree}}\n|{{IPA|[kri\u02d0]}}\n|heart\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|cride}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|cro\u00ed}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|cridhe}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|dooinney}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8d\u032aun\u02b2\u0259]}}\n|person\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|duine}}, cf. Ir., Sc.G {{lang|ga|duine}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|dreeym}}\n|{{IPA|[d\u032ari\u02d0m], [d\u032ari\u1d47m]}}\n|back\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. dative {{lang|sga|druimm}}, nominative ''dromm''; cf. Ir. ''drom'', dialect {{lang|ga|droim}}, dative ''droim'', Sc.G. ''drom'', dialect {{lang|gd|druim}}, dative ''druim''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|duillag}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8d\u032aol\u02b2a\u0261]}}\n|leaf\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|duille\u00f3g}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|duille\u00f3g}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|duilleag}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|eairk}}\n|{{IPA|[e\u02d0ak]}}\n|horn\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|adarc}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|adharc}}, Ir. dialect aidhearc\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|eayst}}\n|{{IPA|[e\u02d0s]}}\n|moon\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|\u00e9sca}}; cf. archaic Ir. {{lang|ga|\u00e9asca}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|easga}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|eeast}}\n|{{IPA|[ji\u02d0s]}}\n|fish\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|ga|\u00edasc}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|iasc}}, Ul. {{lang|ga|/ji\u0259sk/}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|iasg}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ennym}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8en\u0259m]}}\n|name\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|ainmm}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|ainm}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|faarkey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8f\u00f8\u02d0\u0279k\u0259]}}\n|sea\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|fairrge}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|farraige}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|fairge}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|faiyr}}\n|{{IPA|[fe\u02d0\u0259]}}\n|grass\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|f\u00e9r}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|f\u00e9ar}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|feur}}, {{lang|gd|fiar}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|famman}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8faman]}}\n|tail\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|femm}}+ ''-\u00e1n'' nominaliser (masculine diminutive); cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|feam}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|feaman}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|fedjag}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8faia\u0261]}}\n|feather\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|ete\u00f3c}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|eiteog}} \"wing\", Sc.G. {{lang|gd|iteag}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|feeackle}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8fi\u02d0\u0263\u0259l]}}\n|tooth\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|f\u00edacail}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|fiacail}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|feill}}\n|{{IPA|[fe\u02d0l\u02b2]}}\n|meat\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. dative {{lang|sga|fe\u00f3il}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|feoil}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|fe\u00f2il}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|fer}}\n|{{IPA|[fer]}}\n|man\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|fer}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|fear}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|fliaghey}}\n|{{IPA|[fl\u02b2a\u02d0\u0263\u0259]}}\n|rain\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|flechud}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|fleachadh}} \"rainwater; a drenching\", related to ''fliuch'' \"wet\"\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|folt}}\n|{{IPA|[folt\u032a]}}\n|hair\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|folt}}, Ir.''folt'', Sc.G. ''falt''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|fraue}}\n|{{IPA|[fr\u00e6\u02d0w]}}\n|root\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|ga|fr\u00e9m}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|fr\u00e9amh}}, {{lang|ga|pr\u00e9amh}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|freumh}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|fuill}}\n|{{IPA|[fol\u02b2]}}\n|blood\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|fuil}}, Ir., Sc.G. ''fuil''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|geay}}\n|{{IPA|[\u0261i\u02d0]}}\n|wind\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. dative {{lang|sga|ga\u00edth}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|gaoth}}, dative ''gaoith''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|geinnagh}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8\u0261\u02b2an\u02b2ax]}}\n|sand\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|gainmech}}; cf. Sc.G. {{lang|gd|gainmheach}}, Ir. ''gaineamh''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|glioon}}\n|{{IPA|[\u0261l\u02b2u\u02d0n\u02b2]}}\n|knee\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. dative {{lang|sga|gl\u00fain}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|gl\u00fain}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|gl\u00f9n}}, dative ''gl\u00f9in''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|grian}}\n|{{IPA|[\u0261ri\u02d0n], [\u0261ri\u1d48n]}}\n|sun\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|gr\u00edan}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|grian}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|jaagh}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8d\u0292\u00e6\u02d0ax]}}\n|smoke\n|Goidelic, from M.Ir. {{lang|mga|deathach}} < O.Ir. {{lang|sga|d\u00e9}}; cf. Sc.G. {{lang|gd|deathach}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|joan}}\n|{{IPA|[d\u0292aun]}}\n|dust\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|dend}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|deannach}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|kay}}\n|{{IPA|[k\u02b2\u00e6\u02d0]}}\n|fog\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|ce\u00f3}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|ceo}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|ce\u00f2}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|keayn}}\n|{{IPA|[ki\u1d48n]}}\n|sea\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|c\u00faan}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|cuan}} \"harbor\", Sc.G. {{lang|gd|cuan}} \"ocean\"\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|keeagh}}\n|{{IPA|[ki\u02d0x]}}\n|breast\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|c\u00edoch}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|c\u00edoch}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|c\u00ecoch}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|keyll}}\n|{{IPA|[ki\u02d0l\u02b2], [kel\u02b2]}}\n|forest\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|caill}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|coill}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|coille}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|kione}}\n|{{IPA|[k\u02b2aun], [k\u02b2o\u02d0n]}}\n|head\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|cend}}, dative ''ciond''; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|ceann}}, dative ''cionn''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|laa}}\n|{{IPA|[l\u00e6\u02d0]}}\n|day\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|l\u00e1a}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|gd|l\u00e1}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|latha}}, {{lang|gd|l\u00e0}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|laue}}\n|{{IPA|[l\u00e6\u02d0w]}}\n|hand\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|ga|l\u00e1m}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|l\u00e1mh}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|l\u00e0mh}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|leoie}}\n|{{IPA|[l\u00f8i]}}\n|ashes\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. dative {{lang|sga|l\u00faaith}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|luaith}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|luath}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|logh}}\n|{{IPA|[l\u0252\u02d0x]}}\n|lake\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|loch}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|lurgey}}\n|{{IPA|[l\u00f8\u0279\u0261\u0259]}}\n|leg\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|lurga}} \"shin bone\"; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|lorga}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|maidjey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8ma\u02d0\u0292\u0259]}}\n|stick\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|maide}}, Ir., Sc.G. ''maide''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|meeyl}}\n|{{IPA|[mi\u02d0l]}}\n|louse\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|m\u00edol}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|m\u00edol}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|mial}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|mess}}\n|{{IPA|[me\u02d0s]}}\n|fruit\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|mes}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|meas}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|moddey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8ma\u02d0\u00f0\u0259]}}\n|dog\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|ga|matrad}}; cf. Ir. ''madra'', N.Ir. ''mada'',''madadh'' [madu], Sc.G. {{lang|gd|madadh}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|moir}}\n|{{IPA|[m\u0252\u02d0\u0279]}}\n|mother\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|m\u00e1thir}}; cf. Ir. ''m\u00e1thair'', Sc.G. {{lang|gd|m\u00e0thair}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|mwannal}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8monal]}}\n|neck\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|muin\u00e9l}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|muine\u00e1l}}, ''muin\u00e9al'', Sc.G. {{lang|gd|muineal}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|oie}}\n|{{IPA|[ei], [i\u02d0]}}\n|night\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|adaig}} (accusative {{lang|sga|aidchi}}); cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|o\u00edche}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|oidhche}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ooh}}\n|{{IPA|[au], [u\u02d0]}}\n|egg\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|og}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|ubh}},{{lang|ga|ugh}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|ugh}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|pait\u00e7hey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8p\u00e6t\u0283\u0259]}}\n|child\n|French; from E.M.Ir. {{lang|sga|p\u00e1itse}} \"page, attendant\" < O.Fr. {{lang|frm|page}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|p\u00e1iste}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|p\u00e0iste}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|raad}}\n|{{IPA|[r\u00e6\u02d0d\u032a], [ra\u02d0d\u032a]}}\n|road\n|English; from Cl.Ir. {{lang|mga|r\u00f3t}},{{lang|mga|r\u00f3at}}< M.E. {{lang|enm|road}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|r\u00f3d}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|rathad}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|rass}}\n|{{IPA|[ra\u02d0s]}}\n|seed\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|ga|ros}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|rollage}}\n|{{IPA|[ro\u02c8l\u00e6\u02d0\u0261]}}\n|star\n|Goidelic; from M.Ir. {{lang|mga|r\u00e9tlu}} < O.Ir. {{lang|sga|r\u00e9tglu}} + feminine diminutive suffix ''-\u00f3g''; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|r\u00e9alt\u00f3g}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|reultag}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|roost}}\n|{{IPA|[ru\u02d0s]}}\n|bark\n|Brythonic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|r\u00fasc}} Brythonic (cf. Welsh {{lang|cy|rhisg(l)}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|r\u00fasc}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|r\u00f9sg}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|skian}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8ski\u02d0\u0259n]}}\n|wing\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|sc\u00edath\u00e1n}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|sciath\u00e1n}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|sgiathan}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|slieau}}\n|{{IPA|[sl\u02b2u\u02d0], [\u0283l\u02b2u\u02d0]}}\n|mountain\n|Goidelic, from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|sl\u00edab}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|sliabh}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|sniaghtey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8\u0283n\u02b2axt\u032a\u0259]}}\n|snow\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|snechta}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|sneachta}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|sneachd}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|sollan}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8solan]}}\n|salt\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir.,Ir.,Sc.G. {{lang|sga|salann}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|sooill}}\n|{{IPA|[su\u02d0l\u02b2]}}\n|eye\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|s\u00fail}}; cf. Ir. ''s\u00fail'', Sc.G. {{lang|gd|s\u00f9il}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|stroin}}\n|{{IPA|[st\u032aru\u1d48n\u02b2], [st\u032arai\u1d48n\u02b2]}}\n|nose\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. dative {{lang|sga|sr\u00f3in}}; cf. Ir. ''sr\u00f3n'', dialect ''sr\u00f3in'', dative ''sr\u00f3in'', Sc.G. {{lang|gd|sr\u00f2n}}, dative ''sr\u00f2in''\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|tedd}}\n|{{IPA|[t\u032aed\u032a]}}\n|rope\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|t\u00e9t}}; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|t\u00e9ad}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|teud}}, {{lang|gd|tiad}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|thalloo}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8talu]}}\n|earth\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|talam}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|gd|talamh}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ushag}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8o\u0292a\u0261]}}\n|bird\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|uise\u00f3g}} \"lark\"; cf. Ir. {{lang|ga|fuiseog}}, Sc.G. {{lang|gd|uiseag}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|ushtey}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8u\u0283t\u02b2\u0259]}}\n|water\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|ga|uisce}}; cf. Ir. ''uisce'', Sc.G. {{lang|gd|uisge}}\n|-\n|{{lang|gv|yngyn}}\n|{{IPA|[\u02c8i\u014b\u0259n]}}\n|fingernail\n|Goidelic; from O.Ir. {{lang|sga|ingen}}; cf. Ir., Sc.G. {{lang|ga|ionga}}, dative ''iongain'', plural Ir. ''iongna'', Sc.G. ''iongnan'', etc.\n|}\n\nSee [[wikt:Appendix:Celtic Swadesh lists|Celtic Swadesh lists]] for the complete list in all the Celtic languages.\n\n===Loanwords===\n[[File:Manx loaghtan.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Manx Loaghtan|Loaghtan]], a Manx breed of primitive sheep. The name means \"mousy grey\" in Manx.]]\nForeign loanwords are primarily [[Norse language|Norse]] and [[English language|English]], with a smaller number coming from French. Some examples of Norse loanwords are ''garey'' (\"[[garden]]\", from ''[[wikt:gar\u00f0r|gar\u00f0r]]'', \"enclosure\") and ''sker'' meaning a sea rock (from ''[[wikt:sker|sker]]'', compare with ''[[wikt:skj\u00e6r#Etymology 2|skj\u00e6r]]'' and ''[[wikt:sker#Icelandic|sker]]''). Examples of French loanwords are ''danjeyr'' (\"danger\", from ''[[wikt:danger#French|danger]]'') and ''vondeish'' (\"advantage\", from ''[[wikt:avantage|avantage]]'').\n\nEnglish loanwords were common in late (pre-revival) Manx, e.g. ''boy'' (\"boy\"), ''badjer'' (\"[[badger]]\"), rather than the more usual Gaelic ''guilley'' and ''brock''. [[Henry Jenner]], on asking someone what he was doing, was told ''Ta mee smokal pipe'' (\"I am smoking a pipe\"), and that \"[he] certainly considered that he was talking Manx, and not English, in saying it.\" In more recent years, there has been a reaction against such borrowing, resulting in coinages for technical vocabulary. Despite this, [[calque]]s exist in Manx, not necessarily obvious to its speakers.\n\nSome religious terms come ultimately from Latin, Greek and Hebrew, e.g. ''casherick'' (holy), from the Latin ''consecr\u0101tus''; ''mooinjer'' (people) from the Latin ''monasterium'' (originally a [[monastery]]; ''agglish'' (church) from the Greek ''\u1f10\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03b1'' (''ekklesia'', literally meaning assembly) and ''abb'' ([[abbot]]) from the Hebrew \"\u05d0\u05d1\u05d0\" (''abba'', meaning \"father\"). These did not necessarily come directly into Manx, but via Old Irish. In more recent times, ''ulpan'' has been borrowed from [[modern Hebrew]]. Many Irish and English loanwords also have a classical origin, e.g. ''\u00e7hellveeish'' (Irish ''teilef\u00eds'') and ''\u00e7hellvane'' meaning [[television]] and [[telephone]] respectively. Foreign language words (usually known via English) are used occasionally especially for ethnic food, e.g. chorizo, spaghetti.\n\nTo fill gaps in recorded Manx vocabulary, revivalists have referred to modern Irish and Scottish Gaelic for words and inspiration.\n\nGoing in the other direction, Manx Gaelic has influenced [[Manx English]] (Anglo-Manx). Common words and phrases in Anglo-Manx originating in the language include ''tholtan'' (the \"th\" is pronounced as a \"t\") meaning a ruined farmhouse, ''quaaltagh'' meaning a [[first-foot]], ''keeill'' meaning a church (especially an old one), ''[[cammag]]'', ''traa-dy-liooar'' meaning \"time enough\", and [[Tynwald]] (''tinvaal''), which is ultimately of Norse origin, but comes via Manx. It is suggested that the [[House of Keys]] takes its name from ''Kiare as Feed'' (four and twenty), which is the number of its sitting members.\n\n==Comparative vocabulary examples==\n\n<center>\n{| cellspacing=\"7\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! style=\"background:#ffdead;\"| Manx Gaelic\n! style=\"background:#ffdead;\"| Irish\n! style=\"background:#ffdead;\"| Scots Gaelic\n! style=\"background:#ffdead;\"| Welsh\n! style=\"background:#ffdead;\"| English\n|- \n| ''Moghrey mie''\n| {{lang|ga|Maidin mhaith}}\n| {{lang|gd|Madainn mhath}}\n| {{lang|cy|Bore da}}\n| good morning\n|- \n| ''Fastyr mie''\n| {{lang|ga|Tr\u00e1thn\u00f3na maith}}\n| {{lang|gd|Feasgar math}}\n| {{lang|cy|Prynhawn da}}<br />{{lang|cy|Noswaith dda}}\n| good afternoon/evening\n|- \n| ''Slane lhiat'', ''Slane lhiu''\n| {{lang|ga|Sl\u00e1n leat}}, {{lang|ga|Sl\u00e1n libh}}\n| {{lang|gd|Sl\u00e0n leat}}, {{lang|gd|Sl\u00e0n leibh}}\n| {{lang|cy|Hwyl fawr}}\n| goodbye\n|- \n| ''Gura mie ayd'',<br />''Gura mie eu''\n| {{lang|ga|Go raibh maith agat}},<br />{{lang|ga|Go raibh maith agaibh}}\n| {{lang|gd|Tapadh leat}},<br />{{lang|gd|Tapadh leibh}}\n| {{lang|cy|Diolch}}\n| thank you\n|- \n| ''baatey''\n| {{lang|ga|b\u00e1d}}\n| {{lang|gd|b\u00e0ta}}\n| {{lang|cy|cwch}}\n| boat\n|- \n| ''barroose''\n| {{lang|ga|bus}}\n| {{lang|gd|bus}}\n| {{lang|cy|bws}}\n| bus\n|-\n| ''blaa''\n| {{lang|ga|bl\u00e1th}}\n| {{lang|gd|bl\u00e0th}}\n| {{lang|cy|blodyn}}\n| flower\n|- \n| ''booa''\n| {{lang|ga|b\u00f3}}\n| {{lang|gd|b\u00f2}}\n| {{lang|cy|buwch/bo}}\n| cow\n|- \n| ''cabbyl''\n| {{lang|ga|capall}}\n| {{lang|gd|capall}}\n| {{lang|cy|ceffyl}}\n| horse\n|- \n| ''cashtal''\n| {{lang|ga|caisle\u00e1n, caiseal}}\n| {{lang|gd|caisteal}}\n| {{lang|cy|castell}}\n| castle\n|- \n| ''creg''\n| {{lang|ga|carraig}}\n| {{lang|gd|carraig, creag}}\n| {{lang|cy|carreg}}\n| stone\n|- \n| ''eeast''\n| {{lang|ga|iasc}}\n| {{lang|gd|iasg}}\n| {{lang|cy|pysgodyn}}\n| fish [sg.]\n|- \n| ''ellan''\n| {{lang|ga|oile\u00e1n}}\n| {{lang|gd|eilean}}\n| {{lang|cy|ynys}}\n| island, eyot\n|- \n| ''gleashtan''\n| {{lang|ga|gluaiste\u00e1n}}, {{lang|ga|carr}}\n| {{lang|gd|c\u00e0r}}\n| {{lang|cy|car}}\n| car\n|- \n| ''kayt''\n| {{lang|ga|cat}}\n| {{lang|gd|cat}}\n| {{lang|cy|cath}}\n| cat\n|- \n| ''moddey''\n| {{lang|ga|madra}}, {{lang|ga|madadh}}\n| {{lang|gd|madadh}}\n| {{lang|cy|ci}}\n| dog, hound\n|- \n| ''shap''\n| {{lang|ga|siopa}}\n| {{lang|gd|b\u00f9th}}\n| {{lang|cy|siop}}\n| shop\n|- \n| ''thie''\n| {{lang|ga|tigh}}, {{lang|ga|teach}}\n| {{lang|gd|taigh}}\n| {{lang|cy|t\u0177}}\n| house\n|- \n| ''eean''\n| {{lang|ga|\u00e9an}}\n| {{lang|gd|eun}}, {{lang|gd|ian}}\n| {{lang|cy|aderyn}}, {{lang|cy|edn}}\n| bird\n|-\n| ''jees'', ''daa''\n| {{lang|ga|d\u00e1, dh\u00e1, d\u00f3; (people) beirt, d\u00eds}}\n| {{lang|gd|d\u00e0, dh\u00e0; (people) dithis}}\n| {{lang|cy|dau}} (m.)/{{lang|cy|dwy}} (f.)\n| two\n|-\n| ''oik''\n| {{lang|ga|oifig}}\n| {{lang|gd|oifis}}\n| {{lang|cy|swyddfa}}\n| office\n|-\n| ''ushtey''\n| {{lang|ga|uisce}}\n| {{lang|gd|uisge}}\n| {{lang|cy|d\u0175r}}, {{lang|cy|dwfr}}\n| water\n|}\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Language}}\n* [[Cornish language|Cornish]], another revived [[Celtic language]].\n* [[Gaelic revival|Irish language revival]]\n* [[List of Celtic-language media]]\n* [[List of revived languages]]\n* [[List of television channels in Celtic languages]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* <!--Broderick 1984\u201386-->{{Cite book|title=A Handbook of Late Spoken Manx |first=George |last=Broderick |publisher=Niemeyer |location=T\u00fcbingen |year=1984\u201386 |edition=3 volumes |isbn=3-484-42903-8 |id=(vol.&nbsp;1), (vol.&nbsp;2), (vol.&nbsp;3)}}\n* <!--Broderick 1993-->{{Cite book|first=George |last=Broderick |pages=228\u201385 |chapter=Manx |editor=M. J. Ball |editor2=J. Fife |title=The Celtic Languages |publisher=Routledge |location=London |year=1993 |isbn=0-415-01035-7}}\n* {{Cite journal\n|last=Cumming\n|first=Joseph George\n|author-link=Joseph George Cumming\n|year=1848\n|title=The Isle of Man\n|publisher=John Van Voorst\n|publication-date=1848\n|location=London\n|url=https://archive.org/details/isleman00cummgoog\n|ref=harv\n}}\n* <!--Dictionary of the Irish language-->{{cite book|title=Dictionary of the Irish Language based mainly on Old and Middle Irish materials |location=Dublin |publisher=Royal Irish Academy |ur